<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Nuclear Bomb Father Khariton Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Yuly Khariton, one of the
"fathers" of the Soviet (or Russian) nuclear weapons, died
today at the age of 92, the state-run Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Khariton died at 05:00 Moscow time (02:00 GMT) in his home in
Sarov, or Arzamas-16, in Russia's Nizhny Novgorod. Arzamas-16 had
been one of the Russian "closed" cities.
</P>
<P>
The scientist, who had been the head of the nuclear research
center in Arzamas-16 for 45 years, made great contribution in the
development of the first Soviet atomic bomb in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
In 1939, he, in conjunction with Yakov Zeldovich, for the first
time calculated the chain reaction of uranium fission.
</P>
<P>
Although he was second only to Igor Kurchatov among the
"fathers" of the Soviet nuclear weapons, the general public heard
his name for the first time only a few years ago since his name
had been part of classified information as everything he was doing.
</P>
<P>
"The entire life of this many-sided scientist and
indefatigable working man was given to nuclear physics. But he
never liked talking about his work," said Academician Vitaly
Goldansky, head of the Institute of Chemical Physics, also a
colleague and friend of Khariton.
</P>
<P>
The institute was co-founded by Khariton and Nobel prize
winner Nikolai Semyonov.
</P>
<P>
Born in St.Petersburg, Khariton graduated from the Leningrad
Polytechnical Institute in 1925 and studied in the Rutherford
Cavendish Laboratory, Britain, in 1926-28. He began to work in the
Institute of Chemical Physics of the Soviet Union's Academy of
Sciences and other research centers in 1931.
</P>
<P>
He was elected a corresponding member of the Soviet Union's
Academy of Sciences in 1946 and became a full member of the
academy in 1953.
</P>
<P>
He was twice awarded the highest Soviet award of a Hero of
Socialist Labour, and won one Lenin and three State prizes of the
Soviet Union. The academy also rewarded his work with a Lomonosov
Gold medal.
</P>
<P>
Khariton, one of the Soviet (or Russian) nuclear weapon
developers, will be buried at Moscow's Necropolis, Novodevichye
cemetery, next to his wife, on December 23, sources in the
national experimental physics research institute told reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
