<HEADLINE> Tung Chee Hwa Returns to HK from Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 19 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese leaders value
Hong Kong's smooth transition and its long-term prosperity and
stability, said Chief Executive Designate Tung Chee Hwa here today
upon his return from Beijing, where he received the official
certificate on his appointment.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing held at Kai Tak Airport, Tung said that the
grand and cordial reception granted to him in Beijing by top state
leaders showed the importance the country attaches to Hong Kong
and the six million local residents, to Hong Kong's smooth
transition and its long-term prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing tour was brief but fruitful, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday Tung received from Premier Li Peng the order
appointing him as the first Chief Executive of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR). He also met with President
Jiang Zemin and Vice Premier Qian Qichen on separate occasions.
</P>
<P>
The central leaders are very concerned about the stability of
Hong Kong's civil service, he said. "I myself understand this
point too, and hope that the civil service would remain steady."
</P>
<P>
Tung said he will immediately get down to work, preparing for
the formation of the first administration of HKSAR and learning of
people's livelihood.
</P>
<P>
He added that he will meet with Governor Chris Patten and Chief
Secretary Anson Chan as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
On the Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) that is to be
elected Saturday in Shenzhen, Tung called on the British side to
adopt a realistic attitude about the matter and to cooperate with
the PLC.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Junsheng, deputy director of Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong
Branch, was at the airport to greet Tung and his wife.  
</P>
</TEXT>
