<HEADLINE> Russia Denies Comment on FBI Agent's Arrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Foreign Intelligence
Service (FIS) "will not comment" on the reports about the arrest
of the U.S. Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) agent Earl Pitts
for allegedly collaborating with Russian special services, a FIS
spokeswoman said today.
</P>
<P>
Tatyana Samolis, press secretary of FIS Director Vyacheslav
Trubnikov, told reporters that "no intelligence service in the
world ever confirms or denies the involvement of a person in its
operation."
</P>
<P>
Pitts, 43, who has worked with the FBI for 13 years, was
arrested on Wednesday on charges of spying for Russia.
</P>
<P>
U.S. judicial bodies assert that he was recruited by the KGB of
the former Soviet Union in the summer of 1987, and passed over to
Moscow classified defense-related information as well as detailed
reports on FBI staff for their possible recruitment.
</P>
<P>
From 1987 to 1992, when Pitts was reportedly "mothballed," he
received more than 200,000 U.S. dollars from Moscow, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
He was reportedly exposed during a 16-month-long operation
involving a certain Russian U.N. worker who subsequently began to
supply information to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
In response to such charges against FBI officer Pitts, the
Russian FIS chief, Trubnikov said: "Not a single state can exist
without intelligence service," adding that he sees "an underlying
political reason in this exposure."
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that over 400 career officers of foreign
intelligence services were shadowed in Russia over the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
However, Trubnikov stated, Russia will stop conducting
intelligence activities in other countries including the United
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
