<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Economy to Grow by 8 Percent: Mugabe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 19 (Xinhua) -- President Robert Mugabe said
today Zimbabwe's agro-based economy will this year grow by eight
percent.
</P>
<P>
In his state of the nation address to parliament, Mugabe said
the improvement in the country's economic performance has
generally been resulted from the 1995/96 good rainfall season
and high commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''the economic upturn has stimulated renewed
confidence within the agricultural industry and the economy as a
whole. As a result, the economy is expected to register a gross
domestic product growth rate of eight percent in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's agricultural sector, the pillar of the country's
economy, is this year expected to grow by 49 percent, Mugabe
said.
</P>
<P>
He told parliament, ''grain crops made a significant
contribution to this growth with maize production increasing from
839,000 tons in 1994/95 season to 2,609,000 tons while wheat
production increased from 65,000 tons to 250,000 tons.''
</P>
<P>
Tobacco production also rose during the same period from
198,000 to 209,710 tons. Tobacco industry is the largest foreign
currency earner in the country. This year, zimbabwe earned 580
million U.S. dollars from its exports.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said, the manufacturing sector was expected to grow by
3.2 percent in 1996 compared to a decline of 14.2 percent in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the mining sector, he said, mining was expected to
register a decline of 1.1 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe investment center this year approved 304 projects
worth 700 million U.S. Dollars, an increase of 79 percent from
140 million Dollars invested the previous year, he said, adding
the mining sector had accounted for 49 percent of the total
investment in the country.
</P>
<P>
The president stressed, ''in an effort to consolidate these
gains, the government took a number of steps to reduce interest
rates and inflation in order to improve the business operating
environment.''
</P>
<P>
He added, ''the government is paying urgent attention to
restoring macro-economic balance through prudent fiscal and
related monetary policies. These and other measures should create
an enabling environment for increased domestic savings and
investment, including foreign investment.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
