<HEADLINE> HK Wishes to Host Next Year's ITTF Pro-Tour Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong has applied to
host next year's International Table Tennis Federation (ITTF)
Pro-Tour Finals, the head of the Hong Kong Table Tennis
Association (HKTTA) said here Thuresday.
</P>
<P>
An official application was delivered to the ITTF two months
ago, said HKTTA Chairman Tony Yue.
</P>
<P>
Yue said he lobbied during the 1996 Pro-Tour Finals earlier
this month in Tianjin, China, and, from what he was told at the
time, he believes that Hong Kong would most likely win the bid for
the year-end event.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, which hosted the inaugural Women's World Cup earlier
this year, is the only bidder so far for the 1997 Pro-Tour Finals,
Yue said.
</P>
<P>
The year 1997 is of special significance because of Hong Kong's
handover to China. And the HKTTA wishes to see a perfect ending to
the year after participating in April's world championships in
Manchester, Britain, he said.
</P>
<P>
Yue said he is confident of raising enough money for staging
the event, which features the world's top 16 men and women
players.
</P>
<P>
"Various companies have already shown interest in sponsoring
table tennis events in Hong Kong," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, time might be a problem if Hong Kong is authorized to
host the tournament, as the ITTF will not decide on the venue
until the 1997 world championships. That would leave the host just
four months for preparation.
</P>
<P>
HKTTA has already started some initial work for staging the
event, Yue said. "I wish to get ourselves fully prepared in case
we win the bid," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
