<HEADLINE> Mugabe on Resettlement Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 19 (Xinhua) -- President Robert Mugabe said
here today that some 4,000 families had been resettled so far in
the country this year.
</P>
<P>
In his state of the nation address to parliament, he added
that more than 6,000 hectares of land were allocated for
resettlement this year.
</P>
<P>
And a further 64,500 hectares of land will be allocated to
agricultural graduates, a scheme designed to facilitate the entry
of more indigenous farmers into the commercial farming areas,
according to the president.
</P>
<P>
"More importantly, decisions have been taken, and work is now
under way, to accelerate the pace of the implementation of both
land acquisition and resettlement program," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
About 160,000 families needs resettlement since Zimbabwe's
independence in 1980. And so far more than 70,000 families had
been resettled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
