<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Recommendation to Revise US CPI Comes Under Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 19 (Xinhua) -- The recommendation by a
U.S. congressional commission for a downward revision of the U.S.
consumer price index (CPI) is encountering strong criticism from
some economists, The Washington Posts said today.
</P>
<P>
A report by a congressional advisory commission said the CPI
overstated the U.S. inflation and recommended a revision. It was
put forward two weeks ago to the U.S. Senate by the commission
headed by Michael J. Boskin of the Hoover Institute at Stanford
University.
</P>
<P>
But a number of economists have challenged some of the report's
conclusions as inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
Much of the criticism of the report is focused on the claim
that the current CPI overstates the increase in the cost of living
because it misses a significant part of the improvement in the
quality of goods and services, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Critics have also complained about the report's estimates that
the CPI overstates costs of food, housing, new and used cars,
apparel and household appliances.
</P>
<P>
The size of the overstatement "is a gross exaggeration," said
economist Barry Bosworth of the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
The negative reaction from economic experts is politically
important because it will deter the U.S. government from acting on
the commission's recommendation to revise the CPI.
</P>
<P>
Revision of the CPI is a political hot potato because the index
is used to calculate payments that matter to tens of millions of
Americans for federal benefit programs, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
