<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-19 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt To Resist Pound Appreciation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has vowed to deter any
tendency for the Egyptian pound to appreciate against the
U.S. dollar in the wake of heavy capital influx in the last few
months.
</P>
<P>
"The pound is not going to go up. We don't let it appreciate,"
State Minister of the Cabinet Affairs Youssef Boutros Ghali was
quoted by today's Egyptian Gazette as saying.
</P>
<P>
The pound has been steady at about 3.39 to 3.4 pounds to the
dollar for more than two years, with the Central Bank buying
surplus dollars or selling to cover any shortages.
</P>
<P>
Bankers said the Central Bank, acting mainly through the big
four public sector retail banks, has been buying dollars for
several months to balance the foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
Ghali said investments by foreigners has brought in 600 million
to 700 million dollars so far this year and direct foreign
investment leaped to about 2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Most of the investment has been made in the second half of
the year after the government accelerated its privatization
program and the stock market started to rise, according to the
English daily.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank's foreign reserves has risen from 18.5 billion
dollars at the end of June to 18.9 billion dollars at present.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the exchange rate policy was based on
concern for Egyptian exporters, who have found it difficult to
break into foreign market.
</P>
<P>
"Our exporters are used to working in a stable exchange rate
environment. They would find it hard to handle an appreciating
pound environment," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ghali said the interest rate differential between the dollar
and Egyptian pound was no longer the dominant factor in the
pound's resilience to depreciation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
