<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-19 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Rejects Clinton's Criticism of Israel's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu today dismissed U.S. President Bill Clinton's
criticism of his settlement policy, saying such policy would
not change.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the weekly cabinet meeting, Netanyahu said that
his government's policy on settlements had been clear from the
very start. Contrary to Clinton's criticism, Netanyahu said that
Israel's settlement policy did not violate the Oslo accords it
signed with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In the first warning to Israel after his reelection,
Clinton said Monday in Washington that he thought Israel's
settlement policy was preempting a final status agreement, and
was not helpful to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher also expressed his
concern that Israel's new policy to encourage settlement
expansion hinders progress in the Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Despite of the U.S. criticism, Netanyahu said construction
within the existing settlements would continue. But he promised
that there would be no confiscation of land, and any
decision on building new settlements would be made only by
the full cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu rejected the notion that relations between Israel
and the U.S. had been soured by the recent developments,
especially after Israeli government's decision last week to provide
economic incentives to the settlers in order to encourage the
settlement expansion.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite of the difference of opinions over
settlement issue, Israel and the U.S. would work closely to
advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In sharper terms, Tourism Minister Moshe Katzav slammed the
U.S. criticism of Israel's settlement policy as a "grave
mistake," saying it only served to harden the position of
extremist Arabs.
</P>
<P>
To play down the significance of the U.S. criticism, Netanyahu
said the problem facing the government was only one of
public relations. He called on the ministers to do a better
job to explain Israel's position.
</P>
<P>
A public relations campaign has already been under way by
the Netanyahu government, which is facing increasing diplomatic
problems because of its hardline policies that have stalled
the peace process on all tracks.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister David Levy is visiting Jordan today in a
bid to ease the tension between the two countries. Meanwhile,
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai will travel to Cairo next
Tuesday to mend the increasingly tense relations with Egypt.
</P>
</TEXT>
