<HEADLINE> Chirac Strongly Condemns Hostage-Taking in Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 19 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
today strongly condemned the hostage-taking in the residence of
the Japanese ambassador in the Peruvian capital of Lima by members
of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA).
</P>
<P>
Chirac expressed his sympathy with the governments of Peru and
Japan in two messages sent to Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori
and Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, said the press
service of the presidential office.
</P>
<P>
"I don't doubt that your government will do everything
necessary to put things under control with both humaneness and
required firmness," said Chirac in his message addressed to
Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
He said that France is shocked on hearing the news and will
offer Peru its solidarity throughout this test.
</P>
<P>
In his message sent to Hashimoto, Chirac said that France
stands by the side of Japan "in this sorrowful test."
</P>
<P>
He said that Paris believes that a rapid solution will be found
to "this vile and cowardly hostage-taking."
</P>
<P>
About 15 members of the MRTA infiltrated the residence of the
Japanese ambassador Tuesday evening, taking about 500 people
hostage.
</P>
<P>
Most of the hostages have been released, while some 120
hostages, most of them Japanese and Japanese-Peruvians, are still
being held by the guerillas.
</P>
<P>
The guerillas demand the release of some 500 MRTA guerillas
jailed by the government, and abandoning of the neo-liberal
economic policy adopted by President Fujimori. 
</P>
</TEXT>
