<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uneasy Calm Returns to Mogadishu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Uneasy calm returned to
Somalia' capital of Mogadishu today after six days of bitter
fighting among rival factions, but local residents say fighting
may flare up again at any moment.
</P>
<P>
Pedestrians could be seen in the South Mogadishu's hot spot of
Medina for the first time in nearly a week and local residents
who had been hiding under concrete buildings from the shelling
appeared in shops to buy some food.
</P>
<P>
The reason for cease-fire is not clear, but it was believed
that militiamen loyal to Hussein Mohamed Aidid and the Peace
Alliance formed by Osman Atto and Ali Mahdi Mohamed are currently
re-organizing themselves for a showdown to gain control of some
strategic areas in South Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The North Mogadishu faction led by Ali Mahdi also joined the
fighting by exchanging shellings with Aidid's troops in a bid to
support the initiative of the so-called Peace Alliance.
</P>
<P>
Some sources say the warring sides are running short of
ammunition that might also be attributed to the temporary
cease-fire. Others say the faction soldiers of the rival parties
are busy in planting land mines so as to gain time for stronger
militia build-up.
</P>
<P>
So far there is little information about the sources of
weapons and ammunition for the warring factions since the United
Nations had imposed arms embargo on Somalia in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The break for the fighting has enabled families trapped in the
battle zones to flee the area. But Despite the uneasy calm, the
explosions of a few mortar rounds could still be heard in the
residential areas of South Mogadishu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
