<HEADLINE> Death Toll Reaches 15 in UK Food Poisoning Outbreak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Two more people have died in
the E-coli food poisoning outbreak in Lanarkshire, Scotland,
taking the death toll to 15, according to a BBC television report
today.
</P>
<P>
The Lanarkshire Health Board said that a 76-year-old man and a
78-year-old woman died Wednesday evening in Monklands District
General Hospital in the Scottish town of Airdrie.
</P>
<P>
All the 15 victims in the second worst E-coli food poisoning
outbreak ever recorded in the world have all been elderly, local
health official said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that almost 400 people had reported symptoms of
the food poisoning, which can cause kidney failure in vulnerable
people such as the elderly and young children.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman added that 178 people in the area were now
confirmed as suffering from the bug, an increase of 15 from
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to medical experts, E-coli is a bacteria normally
found in the guts of cattle, sheep and people. It is usually
harmless, but a toxic strain that lives in cattle can be passed to
human via manure or improper slaughtering.
</P>
<P>
The two Scottish butcher's shops which were linked to the
crisis reportedly have been closed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Retail Sales Rise 3.9 Pct in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Retail sales volumes in Britain
rose by 0.7 percent in November after a 0.5 percent rise in
October, the biggest monthly increase since June, according to the
latest figures from the Office for National Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The rise was larger than the 0.5 percent increase most experts
were expecting and took the annual retail sale growth to 3.9
percent in November.
</P>
<P>
Sales of clothing and footwear recorded the strongest
increases, rising 2 percent last month and 7.3 percent up on the
same month last year.
</P>
<P>
Household goods continued to benefit from the recovery in the
housing market, rising about 11 percent in cash terms compared
with a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Department stores sales were also buoyant, rising 1.1 percent
in the month.
</P>
<P>
Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke welcomed the
figures, saying that consumers were "spending with confidence" but
that the rise was in line with government forecasts.
</P>
<P>
However, the continuing strength of consumer demand is likely
to fuel fears that retailers may try to rebuild their profit
margins as there was some evidence of this in the clothing and
footwear sector which saw a record price rise in September.
</P>
<P>
The retail sales figures, together with Wednesday's news of a
huge fall in unemployment, also raised economists' expectations
that base interest rates will have to rise again in the new year.
</P>
</TEXT>
