<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Trade Deficit Drops to 7.99 Bln Dlrs in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 19 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. trade deficit
dropped dramatically to 7.99 billion U.S. dollars in October, the
smallest since March, according to a report from the Commerce
Department here today.
</P>
<P>
The department reported that the monthly deficit declined by
30.2 percent from the previous month's imbalance of 11.44 billion
dollars, which set the second worst showing on record.
</P>
<P>
U.S. exports increased by 4.2 percent to a record 71.74 billion
dollars while imports decreased by a slight 0.7 percent to 79.72
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. trade deficit with Japan in the month shot up
by 30.9 percent to 4.96 billion dollars, which was the worst
performance in 14 months, largely due to a big rise in imports of
autos and auto parts from Japan.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. deficit with China widened for a seventh consecutive
month, going up 3.5 percent to 4.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Much of the deficit this year has been from a surge in
America's foreign oil bill, reflecting rising prices. For October,
oil imports rose 5.1 percent to 6.27 billion dollars, the highest
level since November 1990 during the Persian Gulf crisis. The
average price per barrel of crude oil climbed to 21.38 dollars,
the highest level since January 1991.
</P>
<P>
On the export side, shipments of commercial airliners more than
doubled in October, climbing to 1.75 billion dollars. The increase
of 990 million dollars represented almost half the total gain in
exports for the month. Besides, exports of telecommunications
equipment and computer chips also showed big gains during the
month.
</P>
<P>
The overall deficit of 7.99 billion dollars was the smallest
monthly imbalance since a 7.87 billion dollar deficit in March.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the U.S. trade deficit is running at an
annual rate of 113.4 billion dollars, 7.9 percent higher over the
1995 deficit of 105.1 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Condemns Taking Hostages in Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 19 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General
Boutros Boutros-Ghali has written to Peruvian President Alberto
Fujimori to condemn the taking of hostages, as all acts of
terrorism, in the residence of the Japanese ambassador to Peru, a
UN spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Ahamad Fawzi, deputy spokesman for the secretary-general, said
that the UN chief expressed his "most profound concern" about the
situation created by the taking of hostages in the residence of
the ambassador of Japan.
</P>
<P>
In a letter dated Wednesday, Boutros-Ghali expressed his
solidarity with the people of Peru and his support for all efforts
to bring about a peaceful resolution of the crisis through the
immediate and unconditional release of all hostages, according to
the letter.
</P>
<P>
A group of guerrillas took hundreds of international
dignitaries hostage Tuesday night as the Japanese ambassador
hosted a reception in honor of the Japanese emperor's birthday.
The guerrillas demanded that the Peruvian government release their
jailed comrades. 
