<HEADLINE> Egypt Expands Use of Natural Gas As Car Fuel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Egypt is undertaking an
ambitious plan to expand the use of natural gas as fuel for cars,
particularly in the governorates that have natural gas pipelines.
</P>
<P>
Speaking today at the inauguration of an oil complex at Ameria,
west of Egypt's second largest city Alexandria, Oil Minister
Hamdy el-Banbi said his ministry was keen to protect the Egyptian
environment from pollution and make economic use of the huge
potentials of natural gas in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Also today, the minister opened the first gas filling station
in Alexandria, which can serve 50 cars every hour.
</P>
<P>
An agreement between the Petroleum Ministry and Nasser Bank has
provided soft loans to enable car owners to convert to using
natural gas, according to the Egyptian Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will also expand the use of natural gas in houses
and bakeries to protect the environment and upgrade bread quality.
</P>
<P>
Local consumption of natural gas reached 12.3 billion cubic
meters in 1995-96, a three percent increase compared to the
previous year, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's proven natural gas reserves are estimated at 328.3
billion cubic meters, while its gas pipelines reaching 2,000
kilometers.  
</P>
