<HEADLINE> Tanzania Imposes Strict Monitoring of Transit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 19 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania Revenue
Authority (TRA) is imposing strict monitoring of transit cargo
passing through the country to ensure compliance of transit and
tax regulations.
</P>
<P>
Among measures to be taken, according to TRA Chief Counsel,
Mushengezi Nyambele, is to install communication equipment for
monitoring movement of transit cargo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters today, Nyambele said preparations for
the project,
</P>
<P>
which is funded by the World Bank, were at top gear and that
the control of transit cargo both inland and at exit stations
should be in place by next March.
</P>
<P>
The communication equipment will enable TRA security officials
communicate between stations set up along the relevant routes, he
addd.
</P>
<P>
Nyambele said there will also be patrol vehicles supervising
the exercise.
</P>
<P>
He said the whole thing might sound expensive but is rlatively
cheaper than the tax evasion through goods diversion which is
very rampant in the country, particularly on second hand clothes
and oil cargo.
</P>
<P>
A number of unscrupulous traders obtain rubber stamp
indicating the cargo has left the country and another stamp from
the country of destination while in real sense it is sold within
the country, he elaborated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
