<HEADLINE> ICRC Acts as Intermediary to Resolve Hostage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 19 (Xinhua) -- The International Committee of
the Red Cross (ICRC) has been asked by the Peruvian government and
the gurrillas who have been holding hostages at the Japanese
ambassador's residence in Lima to act as a neutral intermediary in
the negotiations to resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued today by the Geneva-based
ICRC, the head of the ICRC delegation in Peru Michel Minnig, who
was among the guests invited to attend the reception held at the
residence, has succeeded in securing the release of some 250 women
and elderly persons and about 50 men. Minnig later arranged for
medical supplies, food and water and toiletries to be brought into
the residence to improve conditions for the people inside.
</P>
<P>
ICRC has also drawn up a list of some 380 hostages and
collected messages from them to deliver to their anxious families,
ICRC said. The ICRC delegates are able to enter and leave the
residence freely to carry out their humanitarian work, it said.
</P>
<P>
ICRC has already handed over to the Peruvian authorities a
document written by members of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary
Movement (MRTA) who sneaked into the reception and held hundreds
of guests there hostage on Wednesday. The document has also been
signed by the hostages themselves.
</P>
<P>
"At present ICRC is continuing to talk with both sides, but is
not taking an active part in the negotiations," said ICRC. It
called on the parties to undertake the firm commitment not to
resort to force or take any steps that may harm the hostages or
hamper its delegates' freedom of movement into and out of the
residence.
</P>
<P>
A crisis unit has been set up at ICRC headquarters in Geneva.
It is in constant contact with its delegation in Lima and is
closely following developments in the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
