<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Opens First Non-profit Umbilical-cord Blood Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Canada has set up its first
non-profit program to store the blood from the umbilical cords of
infants to treat potential future illnesses.
</P>
<P>
Blood from the placenta of a newborn is rich in stem cells,
which are able to reproduce all the types of blood cells. Having
enough of these cells become important if the bone marrow where
blood forms must be replaced during cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
At present, if a marrow transplant is needed, a Canadian family
must find a match from a central registry, which is possible in
only 40 percent of cases, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The body will reject cells that are not compatible, causing
dangerous side effects. These would be no rejection using a
child's own cells.
</P>
<P>
A major advantage of cord cells from newborns is that they have
not yet been exposed to infections. Cord cells from one child
might also be used in treatment of another child in the family.
</P>
<P>
The program is to store the blood cells for only 10 years,
although theoretically there is no limit to storage.
</P>
<P>
The bank was set up by Toronto Hospital in association with
Mount Sinai Hospital and Women's College Hospital in Canada's
largest city of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
The program is voluntary and the hospital charges about 440
U.S. dollars for registration consultations, collection and
storage blood after birth. From then on, the cost of frozen
storage is 73 dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Two commercial blood-bank programs have been set up in Canadian
provinces of British Columbia and Alberta. Both offer to store
cord blood among their services, but the cost is much higher.
</P>
<P>
Non-profit cord blood banks similar to Toronto's have been
established in New York and Paris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OECD Predicts Three Percent Growth Rate for Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Greece will have a growth rate
of about three percent in 1997 but is in danger of maintaining an
increased public deficit, high inflation and unemployment and a
drop in competitiveness, an Athens News Agency (ANA) dispatch from
Paris said today quoting the Organization for Economic Cooperation
and Development (OECD) report.
</P>
<P>
The report said the growth rate reached 2.5 percent in 1996,
which is higher than the European Union average, thanks to an
increase in public investments supported by EU funds.
</P>
<P>
However, the report notes, inflation stood at 8.5 percent,
higher than the government's convergence target, while efforts to
limit the public deficit to 7.6 percent of GDP in 1996 will be
"difficult to attain".
</P>
<P>
Consequently, the target of 4.2 percent for 1997 is in danger
of being missed, according to the OECD, which estimates that the
deficit is not expected to be reduced by more than 1.5 percent
next year.
</P>
<P>
The report also refers to "uncertainties" which exist
concerning a reduction in interest rates and the rate of
de-escalation of inflation, despite the declared intention of the
government to persist with its "hard drachma" policy.
</P>
<P>
Expansion of production "may not be enough to avert a rise in
unemployment, due to the fact that undertakings are continuing
their process of restructuring", the OECD report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economy of Latin America Resumes Moderate Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Latin America and the
Caribbean returned to the path of moderate growth with stable
prices in 1996, the Economic Commission for Latin America and
Caribbean (ECLAC) reported here today.
</P>
<P>
ECLAC estimated that average growth in the region as a whole
reached some 3.5 percent and average inflation fell to 20 percent.
More than half the countries registered single-digit price
increases in 1996.
</P>
<P>
It attributed the growth to a sustained expansion of exports
and to greater access to external finance. Regional exports of
goods reached 248 billion dollars, 11 percent more than 1995.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit, which was equal to 2 percent of
regional GDP, was compensated for by capital inflows of some 50
billion dollars, according to ECLAC.
</P>
<P>
The 20 percent inflation rate in 1996 was the lowest since the
beginning of the 1970s. The average regional inflation rate had
decreased constantly in recent years, from 888 percent 1993 to 337
percent in 1994 and 26 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
ECLAC noted that majority of the governments in the region gave
priority to keep economic stability by adopting fiscal and
monetary policies as main instruments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
