<HEADLINE> US Security Team Dispatched to Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 20 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. security team has
been dispatched to Peru to end a hostage crisis involving several
hundreds of diplomats and officials including seven Americans.
</P>
<P>
The team of more than one dozen hostage-rescue specialists,
which was sent to Lima Thursday, was made up of Federal Bureau of
Investigation (FBI) agents, Pentagon special operations forces and
intelligence experts.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said that the security officials' principal task
will be to advise the U.S. Embassy on ways to protect the
estimated 10,000 Americans living in Peru, but they will also be
available to advise the Peruvian government if requested.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said the American
forces were sent "as a precaution" and to help "get through any
contingencies."
</P>
<P>
U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno said that the FBI and the
Justice Department have been working with the State Department and
National Security Council staff to handle the crisis.
</P>
<P>
A group of guerrillas belonging to the Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary Group stormed the residence of the Japanese
ambassador during a Christmas party Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Although they have released hundreds of hostages, the group
says it still holds several hundred others and will begin killing
them unless all their compatriots are released from prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
