<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multi-Party System Not for Singapore: PM Goh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's fundamental
strength is a "strong, fair and forward-looking government," Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong said here today, challenging the idea of a
multi-party system for Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Speaking tonight to some 1,000 students at the Nanyang
Technological University (NTU) on "Singapore's Dream and
Singaporeans' Dream," Goh said Singapore would not have
accomplished half of what it did in the last 30 years if the
country "had a multi-party system and a revolving-door
government."
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that Singapore's progress would have been
affected if there were ten to 20 opposition members who always
held the government in check. Precious time and much energy would
be wasted engaging dishonest politicians in the parliament, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the prime minister's comments came
just shortly ahead of the impending general election which he is
expected to announce early next week.
</P>
<P>
"The best bed for Singaporeans to dream is the one built by
capable, honest, and committed men and women," Goh said.
</P>
<P>
He also told the students that his government would ensure them
enjoying "the fruits of meritocracy."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also promised the young students that the
government "will give them more space to do their own things, and
encourage more street life and performances."
</P>
<P>
"We should encourage roadside portraits artists, calligraphers
and open-air performances. We should bring back exotic crafts like
snake-charmers. We can do with more spontaneity and creativity,
and more interesting night life. We will allow neon-light and
liquid-crystal advertising to brighten up selected entertainment
areas", he said.
</P>
<P>
Goh, however, also encouraged the students to "be more
independent and rely less on the government," as the 21st century
will usher in a "tougher and more competitive world."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
