<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1.5 Million Chinese Lay-offs Re-employed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Ministry of Labor
said recently that 1.5 million laid-off workers as a result of the
country's massive economic restructuring campaign have found new
jobs this year.
</P>
<P>
Through the "Re-employment Project" launched by the country's 22
provinces and autonomous regions, China has succeeded in keeping
its unemployment rate below three percent.
</P>
<P>
China has given top priority to the re-employment of laid-off
personnel, and encourages the countryside to digest the surplus
rural labor forces in order to alleviate pressure on urban
employment.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that in the 1996-2000 period, China faces a
heavy employment pressure.
</P>
<P>
During that period, China will use every possible means to
create job opportunities for another eight million urban
residents, and encourage 2.5 million laid-off or redundant workers
to participate in the new jobs project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
