<HEADLINE> Swedish Economy Mixed: OECD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, December 20 (Xinhua)-- Economists from the
Organization for Economic Cooperation (OECD) warned that Sweden's
lofty wage costs impose a major threat to its exports and
financial market, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
The warning comes in the latest six-monthly report "Economic
Outlook."
</P>
<P>
The OECD warns that the most recent wage settlements were
higher than the Swedish economy can cope with and that future wage
agreements must be much lower, or exports will be afflicted.
</P>
<P>
Higher wage costs will lead companies to raise prices, which
will make Swedish commodities more expensive and less competitive
in international market.
</P>
<P>
Higher inflation expectations caused by the high wage costs
would also threaten the credibility Sweden has gained on the
financial market, which has provided the country with long-term
loans at low interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The report also contained positive comments on Sweden,
regarding the budget and the balance on the current account. The
state budget is heading towards a balance in 1998 and the surplus
on the current account is expected to increase from 0.3 percent of
the GDP this year to 4.5 percent in 1998. Only four out of 27 OECD
countries can beat this figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
