<HEADLINE> China to Receive Information from Five More Satellites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The China Remote Sensing
Satellite Ground Station (CRSGS) will receive transmissions from
five more satellites in the next five years, to bring the number
to nine from original four.
</P>
<P>
Xu Guanhua, vice-minister of the Chinese Scientific and
Technological Commission, made the announcement here today at the
station's 10th anniversary celebration.
</P>
<P>
The five new satellites are the Canadian Radarsat, the French
Spot, the American Landsat Seven, a satellite with one meter
resolution, and a Chinese satellite that will be launched in 1998.
</P>
<P>
At present, the station receives transmissions from four
satellites: the American Landsat Five, a Japanese craft and two
from Europe.
</P>
<P>
The only civil satellite ground station in China, CRSGS has
received nearly 200,000 TM images and 35,000 pieces of SAR
data. It has also contributed to the production of 7,600 tapes,
more than 1,000 discs, and 35,000 photos, both color, and black
and white.
</P>
<P>
Its sales volume ranks second among the 17 satellite ground
stations in the world.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, space remote sensing has entered all
professions related to earth resources and the ecological
environment, such as agriculture, forestry, geology, petroleum,
and oceanography.
</P>
<P>
Satellite remote sensing images also provide services for which
there are no substitutions, such as land surveying, crop yield
assessment and disaster monitoring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
