<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 17th Meeting of SAARC Foreign Ministers Concludes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The two-day 17th meeting of
foreign ministers of South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) concluded here this evening, deciding to speed
up economic and trade cooperation among the member nations.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers decided to immediately launch the third
round of trade negotiations for tariff concessions in the region.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to finalize an action plan at the earliest to
expedite the creation of a South Asian free trade area (SAFTA)
before the targeted year 2000. These decisions are expected to
give a big boost to intra-regional economic and trade cooperation
and development.
</P>
<P>
At the 8th summit of SAARC held here in May last year, all the
member nations agreed to set up a South Asian preferential trading
arrangement (SAPTA) in the region and approved it at the end of
last year. In the first two rounds of trade negotiations for
tariff concessions among the member nations, 2,000 tariff lines
for preferential treatment among the member nations have been
agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
The 8th summit also proposed to set up a South Asian free trade
area in the region by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Briefing newsmen here this evening, Indian External Affairs
Minister I.K. Gujral said that the actions undertaken by all the
SAARC countries after launching the South Asian preferential
trading arrangement last year showed there was convincing evidence
that all countries are committed to moving forward.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in 1985, embraces Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the
Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
