<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Signs Expanded Value Added Tax Into Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos signed into law here today a bill which amended the Value
Added Tax Law of the country.
</P>
<P>
The new law is a more equitable, broader-based and less
graft-prone taxation system that would sustain the country's
requirements for service delivery and community development, he
said.
</P>
<P>
With the approval of this vital piece of legislation, Ramos
said, the basic qualities of the value-added tax (VAT) is upheld,
the very reasons that the country shifted to the VAT system eight
years ago.
</P>
<P>
"The VAT works efficiently when it is broad-based, which was
why we had to expand the scope of the original VAT," he said.
"However, it is necessary that we ensure genuine equity in the
system."
</P>
<P>
Since its enactment and implementation in 1988, the VAT system
has provided a buoyant revenue base, he said, adding that in 1995
alone it raised some 28.8 billion pesos (1.07 billion U.S.
dollars) or 9.3 percent of the country's total revenue and is
expected to generate more than twice that amount this year.
</P>
<P>
While expanding its base, however, the new law exempts items
such as medical, dental, hospital and veterinary services not
rendered by professionals; educational services given by private
and government educational institutions; art; literary works;
musical compositions; and sale, importation and publication of
some books and magazines.
</P>
<P>
It also exempts houses and lots valued less than 1 million
pesos (38,168 dollars), coal, natural gas, petroleum products and
raw materials for their manufacture and non-agricultural, marine
and forest products.
</P>
<P>
"Putting our taxation system in order is imperative if we are
to ensure a solid government fiscal position over the long run.
Without a more rational tax policy, our country can not sustain
the gains it has reaped in recent years," the president said.
</P>
</TEXT>
