<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Says It Has Enough Power to Survive Winter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Spurred by a fuel shortage and
daily electricity cut-offs, the Energy and Fuel Ministry hastily
assured the public that Ukraine has enough power to survive the
winter.
</P>
<P>
About 4 million tons of coal should have been accumulated,
plus 400,000 tons of mazut and 25 billion cubic meters of gas,
said Energy and Fuel Minister Anatoly Minchenko today.
</P>
<P>
He said the volume of fuel accumulated this year equals to last
year's figures, adding the supply would be sufficient to keep the
country warm when temperatures drop.
</P>
<P>
In October, the frequency of the electricity network fell to
48.9 Hertz but has since stabilized at 49.5 Hertz. If the
frequency had continued to drop, it could have led to a collapse
of Ukraine's energy system.
</P>
<P>
Even though the frequency has stabilized, the electricity is
shut off at least two hours every day in 90 percent of Ukraine's
towns and villages.
</P>
<P>
The energy problems are further aggravated by the low profit
margin of the energy sector. "How can we operate with profit of
only 2,37 percent?" said Yury Ulitych, the deputy energy minister.
</P>
<P>
He added the rate of 3.1 cents per kilowatt hour was too low.
The ministry plans to increase the price to 3.6 cents.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, unpaid electricity bills nationwide will total
1.5 million U.S. dollars by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Minchenko said the ministry expects the parliament to ratify
the agreement between Ukraine and the World Bank on a loan of 120
million dollars to buy fuel for thermal power plants.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Ukraine will need about 80 billion cubic meters of
gas, the energy minister said. Ukraine has already agreed to
import 53 billion cubic meters of gas from Russia and 6 billion
cubic meters from Uzbekistan to supplement the country's reserve
of 17 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
He said Ukraine was negotiating an agreement with Turkmenistan
for at least 7 billion cubic meters of gas. So far, Ukraine has
owed Russia gas debts of 564 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
