<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Yemen Achieves Great Success in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The economic, financial and
administrative reform program in Yemen, started in March 1995,
has achieved great successes, actually beyond expectation in
minimizing state budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
The reform program had cut the deficit from 19.147 billion
Yemeni rials (about 152 million U.S. dollars) to 7.122 billion
rials (56.5 million dollars) during the first nine months of the
current year.
</P>
<P>
The program has also scored tangible success in stabilizing
the rate of exchange of the national currency against foreign
currencies, particularly the U.S. dollar. It has also stemmed the
growing inflation.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to control the cash flow, the Yemeni central bank
absorbed more than 8 billion Yemeni rials (63 million dollars) by
issuing Treasury bonds, besides the liberalization of trade,
abolition of import licenses, and encouraging exports. Exports
over the past year amounted to 108 million dollars, as compared
with 40.3 million dollars in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, steps have been taken to embark on the initial phase
of the free zone in Aden at a total cost of 500 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the field of administrative reform and stamping out
corruption and manipulation of public funds, the program has
activated the machinery of control and auditing, and more than
2,000 cases have been referred to public fund courts.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, Yemeni successes in the implementation of
the economic, financial and administrative reform program have
given rise to a state of content and optimism, not only in Yemen
and among the Yemeni people, but also at the level on
international and regional organizations and countries.
</P>
<P>
They highly appreciate the steps and achievements made by
Yemen, so much so that international organizations have decided
to augment their assistance and support for Yemen, and soft loans
to Yemen over the current year have reached 350 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the World Bank has decided to increase its annual
finance to Yemen to 140 million dollars, and the Paris Club has
agreed to drop 67 per cent of the due Yemeni debts. Besides,
positive initiatives have been made by Holland, Japan, France and
Germany to augment their assistance and support to Yemen.
</P>
<P>
Yemen's successes have also prompted local, Arab and foreign
investors to flock to Yemen where the total number of projects
approved by the Yemeni Investment Authority has exceeded 900 with
a total investment cost of more than 211 billion rials (1.67
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Several foreign companies have actually applied to invest in
the free zone of southern Yemeni city of Aden. The value of
these requests has exceeded 1.5 billion dollars, providing job
opportunities to some 10,000 Yemenis.
</P>
<P>
However, economists here believe that despite these
achievements and successes, it cannot be said that everything has
been straightened out or that Yemen has flourished.
</P>
<P>
Yemen is still a poor, developing country. The economic crisis
is there, and the economic struggle has not been decided one way
or the other. It is incumbent upon Yemen, therefore, to pursue
its efforts, and to mobilize all potentials as well as financial
and human resources for the success of the overall economic and
social development, in order to emerge from the vicious circle of
poverty, and to build a prosperous and economically strong
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
