<HEADLINE> ADB Offices Operational in Cambodia, Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) announced here today that its resident offices in Phnom
Penh, Cambodia and in Hanoi, Vietnam began operations respectively
on Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement issued here, the Manila-based bank said
that the ADB Board of Directors approved the establishment of the
resident offices in the two countries earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The ADB is the largest multi-lateral aid lender to Cambodia,
and was the first to extend a loan to the country after the
U.N.-supervised elections there in 1992. Since then, the ADB has
provided Cambodia with nine loans totaling 246 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the bank said that the objective of its
resident mission in Cambodia is to help the Cambodian government
achieve sustainable growth with equity and social justice.
</P>
<P>
The bank also said that the aim of its resident mission in
Hanoi is to promote policy reform, institutional development and
infrastructure development in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam is the largest recipient of the ADB's concessional
assistance and zero-interest loans. Since resuming assistance to
Vietnam in 1993, the bank has approved 13 loans totaling 937
million dollars to the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
