<HEADLINE> Nepali Opposition Warns Against Expulsion of MPs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of Nepal's main
opposition and a former ruling partner today warned against
possible expulsion of two MPs from the lower house.
</P>
<P>
President of the main opposition Communist Party Of Nepal
(United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML) Man Mohan Adhikari and
parliamentary leader of the National Democratic Party (RPP)
Lokendra Bahadur Chand told a press conference today that their
parties will not accept the house speaker's possible decision to
expel two MPs of a third party.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued on the occasion said that the RPP has
withdrawn their support to the present coalition government.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of leaders of the CPN-UML and the RPP met Speaker
Ram Chandra Poudel and Prime Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba, both
from the main ruling Nepali Congress (NC) party, earlier today to
warn against possible dismissal of two Nepal Goodwill Party (NSP)
MPs from the house, the two leaders said.
</P>
<P>
Expulsion of any MPs from the house is unconstitutional at a
time when a special house session has been convened to discuss a
no-confidence motion against the government, they told the press
conference.
</P>
<P>
The NSP party, meanwhile, registered separate letters at the
parliament on Wednesday and Thursday, asking for immediate
expulsion of it's MPs Anish Ansari and Hridyesh Tripathi as they
supported the no-confidence motion filed by the CPN-UML and the
RPP.
</P>
<P>
The two MPs are among the 102 lawmakers who requested King
Birendra to summon the special house session by claiming that they
had lost confidence in the Deuba government.
</P>
<P>
A no-confidence motion requires a majority vote of 103 to pass
in the 205-seat lower house of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The present coalition government was formed in September last
year by the NC, the RPP and the NSP after they jointly overthrew
the minority CPN-UML government through a similar censure motion.
</P>
<P>
The RPP party, with only 19 MPs in the house, will lead a new
ruling coalition if the present NC-led government is ousted
through the motion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
