<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Heading Towards International Shipping Center (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Experts and local officials owe the the rapid growth of the
handling capacity in Shanghai Port to China's reform and
opening-up policy, as well as the opening-up of Pudong New Area,
which has pushed economic development in the entire Yangtze River
Valley.
</P>
<P>
Official sources say that the seven provinces and Shanghai
Municipality produce 40 percent of China's GNP and 21 percent of
the import and export volume, with just 20 percent of the Chinese
territory.
</P>
<P>
The region has maintained 14 to 20 percent in annual economic
growth rates. More than 30 percent of China's foreign investment
has flocked to the region.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has now established trade contacts with more than 160
countries and regions. More than 4,000 overseas enterprises or
institutions have established representative offices, 150 of which
are financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Over 18,000 foreign-funded enterprises have landed in the
largest industrial city, with 50 billion US dollars in contract
investment.
</P>
<P>
With Zhejiang's Beilun Port and Zhoushan Port, in the south of
Shanghai, and Zhangjiagang Port and Nantong Port to the north of
Shanghai, the five closely connected ports can handle 10 million
TEU in containers, forming the bulk of a modern international
shipping center.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Port alone handles one quarter of China's sea cargo
and one third of sea containers. It has started regular cargo
routes to different parts of the world. Some 2,700 domestic and
foreign transportation agencies have opened offices in Shanghai,
and more than 200 institutions are providing services for
them. The world's top ten international shipping companies have
all sailed into Shanghai.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Suspend Imports of Swiss Cattle and Beef </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 20 (Xinhua) -- France will suspend imports of
cattle and beef from Switzerland as a precautionary measure
against BSE, or mad cow disease, said French officials today.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland, the second most Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy
(BSE)-touched country after Britain, registered 240 cases of such
disease since its first appearance 10 years ago. Britain recorded
160,000 BSE cases in the same period.
</P>
<P>
Since January, 45 cases of BSE, whose virus are believed to be
capable of causing a slowly developing but fatal human disease,
occurred in Switzerland, which has culled hundreds of thousands of
cows.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Minister Philippe Vasseur will make an official
announcement of the decision today.
</P>
<P>
The French government will have to wait for an official
decision by the European Union before applying its decision, said
the officials.
</P>
<P>
Germany, Italy and Austria have already banned imports of Swiss
cattle and beefs.
</P>
<P>
France has begun banning living cattle from Switzerland, and
putting strict sanitary controls over entry of beef products from
the neighboring country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Heading Towards International Shipping Center (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 20 (Xinhua) -- China is busy turning its
major port and largest industrial city into an international
shipping center by increasing its handling capacity to 220 million
tons by the end of the century and 280 million tons by the year
2010.
</P>
<P>
According to a city official, Shanghai Port is expected to
raise its container handling capacity from the present 1.9 million
TEU to at least 2.5 million TEU by 2000 and more than six million
by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
To do this, the city plans to put at least ten billion yuan
into dredging the mouth of the Yangtze River, where the port is,
within seven to ten years so that the most up-to-date container
ships then can use it, and 100,000-tonnage freighters can anchor
there.
</P>
<P>
If all goes as planned, experts say, the port, which has been
plagued by a serious sludge problem for half a century, will be a
flourishing international water transport center, Xu Bozhang, an
official in charge of construction of the international shipping
center, says.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the potential international shipping center, Cao
Lansheng, a shipping expert and director of the Planning and
Development Commission of the China Port Association, says that
Shanghai has advantages similar to those of Rotterdam, Hong Kong,
Singapore, and New York, but that the most important thing is how
the port and channel construction go.
</P>
<P>
Referring to other advantages of Shanghai, he said that the
city is a flourishing financial and trade center, and handles 52
billion US dollars worth of goods annually. And, with a 14 to 20
percent annual growth rate in the Yangtze River Delta, and in the
entire Yangtze River valley, the volume of container freight at
the port is growing by 30 percent annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
