<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Factories Urged to Make Environmental Protection Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 20 (Xinhua) -- A leading Chinese official has
called on the country's military industry to switch to production
of environmental protection equipment.
</P>
<P>
With 450 billion yuan due to be spent by China on environmental
protection over the next five years, State Councillor Song Jiang
said that military industry enterprises can play an important role
by launching into the so-called 'sunshine industries'.
</P>
<P>
Song, also minister of State Science and Technology Commission
and chairman of the State Council's Environmental Protection
Committee, made the remark today at an ongoing national
conference on environmental science and technology.
</P>
<P>
He said military industry enterprises have technological and
manufacturing superiority. However, they are short of production
orders and are capable of making other products, not related to
military or defense items.
</P>
<P>
The environmental protection industry has seen rapid growth in
the world, and has been what he called a "sunrise industry."
</P>
<P>
The state councillor said China has entered a period of large
scale environmental protection prevention and treatment, and the
environmental protection industry needs greater development.
</P>
<P>
The country has decided to put 450 billion yuan (59.9 billion
U.S. dollars) into environmental protection by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
China now has some 9,000 factories specializing in
environmental protection facilities and products, but most have
out-of-date techniques and products.
</P>
<P>
Song stressed that advanced technology, both domestic and
overseas, must be introduced into the industry, especially into
the large and medium-sized factories to upgrade China's
environmental protection industry and improve quality of products.
</P>
<P>
Song Jiang also asked the nation's environmental protection
departments to strengthen the administration of the environmental
protection products' market and institute a fair competition
system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
