<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Stays Judgment on President's Rule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The Indian Supreme Court
today stayed a judgment passed by Uttar Pradesh's Allahabad High
Court on Thursday to quash presidential rule in the state.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government filed a petition challenging the high
court judgment in the wake of an order issued by the latter and
the supreme court.
</P>
<P>
In granting an interim stay on the high court order, a
three-judge bench said, "This will not preclude the governor of
Uttar Pradesh from exploring the possibility of forming a popular
government."
</P>
<P>
From the end of October to early November this year, assembly
elections were held in Uttar Pradesh, but no single political
party won a clear majority in the polls. The Bharatiya Janata
Party (BJP) emerged the largest party in the state, but it could
not muster enough support to form a government.
</P>
<P>
To avoid chaos and violence in the state, the central
government decided to re-impose the president's rule there as it
had done before the assembly elections. The parliament approved
the action of the central government, but the BJP challenged the
move in the Allahabad High Court.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
