<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Maintains Strong Growth Momentum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine economy, which
began to pick up three years ago, further gained strength in the
first three quarters in 1996, the National Economic and
Development (NEDA) said today.
</P>
<P>
In a review on economic performance in 1996, the NEDA cited an
impressive increase in the country's gross national product (GNP),
a considerable fall in its inflation rate and improving financial
situation for the government.
</P>
<P>
The GNP, adjusted for inflation, grew by 7.1 during the first
three quarters this year, compared to 5.3 percent a year ago, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The report said the recovery of agriculture and the continued
good performance of the services and industry sectors raised gross
domestic product (GDP) by 5.4 percent from last year's 4.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
Though merchandise trade suffered from a weak demand for
electronics and garments and traditional exports like coconut
products, the hefty growth of non-merchandise exports led to an
23.1 percent expansion in total exports.
</P>
<P>
In another sign of strong economic showing, inflation rate fell
rapidly to single-digit levels in June from more than 10 percent
last year. The inflation rate experienced a record low of 4.4
percent in September and increasing slightly to 4.5 percent by
November.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government will enjoy a financial surplus for
the third consecutive year. As of October 1996, the government's
financial surplus has reached 10.7 billion pesos, 300 million
pesos higher than the amount recorded last year.
</P>
<P>
With inflation in check, combined with sustained improvement in
the government financial operations and stable peso-dollar
exchange rate, the country's interest rates have been on the
downtrend for most of the year.
</P>
<P>
The country's employment situation is also encouraging. The
report said the continued strong economic performance has been
encouraging people to look for jobs.
</P>
<P>
Citing a survey conducted by the NEDA in July, the report said
unemployment rate dropped substantially to 7.7 percent that month
from 8.8 percent a year earlier.  
</P>
</TEXT>
