<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Step up Legislation for Asset Evaluation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 20 (Xinhua) -- China will step up legislation
for the asset evaluation industry in an effort to promote the
healthy development of this sector, the State Administration of
State Property (SASP) announced today.
</P>
<P>
Asset appraising is a new undertaking in China, covering both
what can be seen and what can't, such as fixed assets, land-use
rights, trade marks and industrial property rights, said
Pan Yue, deputy director of the SASP.
</P>
<P>
"All departments must safeguard state interests and stick to
the principle of evaluating assets in accordance with unified
policies and standards, in order to ease the financial burden of
enterprises and optimize the distribution of available assets,"
Pan said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China had 2,893 asset evaluation agencies
employing more than 48,000 professional asset appraisers by the
end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Assets evaluated during the Eighth Five-Year Plan period
(1991-1995) had an account value of over 1.43 trillion yuan (about
173.4 billion US dollars), over 710 billion yuan more than the
number at which they were appraised.
</P>
<P>
However, the excessive participation in asset evaluation by
different departments has wrought chaos in the sector and
increased the financial burden of enterprises, Pan pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"This has ultimately harmed the effort to deepen enterprise
reforms and tarnished China's image in opening up to the rest of
the world," he said, adding that it has also corrupted people's
work habits.
</P>
<P>
"The negative trend must be halted," he noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
