<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Economic Slowdown, of Cyclical Nature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Even tourism was not spared. The number of visitors fell by 4.8
percent, the first decline since the first quarter of 1991. As a
result, retail sales were flat, while restaurants and hotels
registered lower takings during the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
However, in analyzing the economic situation, both the
Singapore government and economists in the private sector agreed
that what the economy was experiencing was more of a short sharp
shock, which was considered a welcome breather, than any prolonged
slump.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong said late last month that the
government was not worried about the current slowdown, because the
country's economic fundamentals were "very strong" and the
downturn in the electronics industry, being cyclical, was expected
to take an upturn next year.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong commented that unlike the
economic recession in 1985, currently, the investment commitments
in Singapore remained strong.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Development Board (EDB) had attracted a total of
6.4 billion Singapore dollars (about 4.6 billion US dollars) of
investment in the first nine months, and by the end of this year,
the figure was expected to exceed the originally target of 7.5
billion Singapore dollars (about 5.36 billion US dollars) to set a
new record of 8 billion Singapore dollars (about 5.7 billion US
dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the deputy prime minister said that Singapore's
domestic economic fundamentals remained sound, while externally,
there were positive signs that the current slowdown would not be
too severe or prolonged.
</P>
<P>
Given such assessment of the present economic situation at
home, the government said that there would be no need to make "any
drastic policy adjustments to cope with the downturn." Rather, it
wanted to maintain "an even course, and accept slower growth for a
few quarters until external demand picks up again."
</P>
<P>
In dealing with the structural changes taking place in some
sectors of the economy, the Singapore government pledged to
continue its efforts in helping companies to upgrade their
operations, re-train workers, and improve their performance to
remain competitive.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the government said the current slowdown had
not changed its longer term assessment that Asia is set to boom
for the next 20 years, that Singapore is well placed to take
advantage of this regional prosperity, and that Singapore's
economy can aim to grow by six to eight percent per year over the
next decade.
</P>
<P>
As for the outlook of next year, the Ministry of Trade and
Industry is expecting the economy to grow by five to seven percent
in 1997, assuming that the electronics industry picks up
world-wide by the latter half of the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
