<HEADLINE> Regulation on Annual Enterprise Check Issued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Limited corporations,
joint-stock companies, and other enterprises and businesses with
service licences in China will have to undergo annual checks from
the new year.
</P>
<P>
Companies disobeying rules and firms failing to attend the
checks, to be conducted between January to April, face measures
that could prevent them expanding and lead to their licences being
cancelled.
</P>
<P>
The announcement has been made in the Regulation on Annual
Enterprise Assessment, issued by China's State Administration for
Industry and Commerce, and will take effect from January 1st next
year.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulation, after the check, enterprises will
be divided into two categories. A-category enterprises will be those
which have a sound performance in adhering to rules and regulations
of the State Administration for Industry and Commerce, and
enterprises that disobey the rules will belong to B-category.
</P>
<P>
B-category enterprises are forbidden to open branches, set up
limited or joint-stock companies, or expand their business in
other ways.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also says that enterprises that do not attend
the check will be banned from any further business, and their
names will be made public. If the enterprises still do not apply
for the check within 30 days, their licences will be revoked.
</P>
<P>
The rule is an effort to strengthen the supervision of
industrial and commercial administration organs on markets and
regulate annual assessments for enterprises, according to
authorities with the State Administration for Industry and
Commerce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
