<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Trade Declines in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's total trade
declined by 1.4 percent in November, when the country saw a sharp
fall of 8.8 percent in its non-oil domestic exports, the Singapore
Trade Development Board (TDB) announced today.
</P>
<P>
It said, however, that on a three-month moving average basis,
total trade at current prices in the month increased marginally by
0.4 percent, while non-oil domestic exports decreased by 4.7
percent, affected by a cyclical downturn in global electronics
demand.
</P>
<P>
Oil domestic exports continued to rise by 23.6 percent as oil
prices remained high and re-exports went up marginally by 1
percent. But on a monthly basis, re-exports shrank by 4.1 percent
and domestic exports of oil jumped by 29.2 percent in November.
</P>
<P>
This was due mainly to the continued surge of 25 percent in oil
prices as demand soared because of cold weather in Europe and the
United States, the TDB said.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil domestic exports, after falling by 4.7 percent, were
valued at 7.3 billion Singapore dollars (about 5.21 billion U.S.
dollars). The decline was reflected in key markets such as the
United States, the European Union, Malaysia, Japan and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, non-oil domestic exports to South Korea and
China remained strong, growing by 11.6 percent and 39.9 percent
respectively, it said.
</P>
<P>
The value of oil domestic exports stood at 1.5 billion
Singapore dollars (about 1.07 billion U.S. dollars) in November,
while that of re-exports was 6.1 billion Singapore dollars (about
4.36 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In November, imports increased marginally by 1 percent to 15.9
billion Singapore dollars (about 11.36 billion U.S. dollars). The
increase was largely in imports of computer parts and peripherals,
disk drives, motorized vessels, blank computer tapes and discs and
other products, the TDB said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
