<HEADLINE> Australia Retains Import Ban on Uncooked Salmon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Australia will retain an
import ban on uncooked salmon products, federal Primary Industries
Minister John Anderson said today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here he said that he had advised the
United States and Canada of the decision taken by the Australian
Quarantine and Inspection Service (AQIS). Both of them have sought
to export uncooked salmon products to Australia.
</P>
<P>
"I fully support the AQIS decision, which is based on
scientific and technical grounds and which is entirely consistent
with Australia's rights under the Sanitary and Phytosanitary
Agreement of the World Trade Organization," he said.
</P>
<P>
The AQIS finalized its decision after an extensive scientific
study of some 24 diseases of salmon, most of which do not exist in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
The AQIS said that an agreement to allow the entry of uncooked
salmon products presented risks substantially greater than would
agreement to many other access requests.
</P>
<P>
It also would be almost impossible to eradicate the diseases if
they became established in Australian waterways, and the diseases
could harm the population of endangered and vulnerable native
salmon species.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
