<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Faster Growth Expected for HK Economy in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's economy would
grow faster in 1997 than this year following the good performance
over the past few months, economic analysts here say.
</P>
<P>
The upward trend of Hong Kong's economy is evident this
year. In the first quarter, the gross domestic product (GDP) only
registered a 3.3 percent rise, but in the second quarter the rise
went up to 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
For the third and fourth quarters, the GDP is expected to rise
by 5.3 percent and 6.2 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
This rising momentum will continue, many analysts believe. In
their recent economic forecasts, Hong Kong Bank projected a 5.2
percent rise in real GDP for 1997, while Hang Seng Bank estimated
the growth to be 5.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other local major financial and economic institutes and many
individual analysts generally hold that the growth would be around
5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The forecast growth rate is much higher than the latest
readjusted official forecast of 4.7 percent for the whole of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Consumption is expected to be a major factor for boosting the
economy in 1997. The local stock and property markets' positive
outlook will help stimulate consumer spending, and tourist income
will also enjoy considerable increases riding on the historical
moment of Hong Kong's return to the motherland in the year.
</P>
<P>
George Leung, economic adviser with Hong Kong Bank, said: "The
rise in domestic consumption since the middle of this year looks
set to continue into 1997, supported by the positive wealth effect
generated by the prosperous local stock and property markets."
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate has been falling steadily this year,
dropping to a low of 2.6 percent in the third quarter. With a
rebound in economic activities, employment opportunities would
continue to grow, which would boost economic confidence and
increase real incomes.
</P>
<P>
Many analysts also hold that the interest rate environment is
likely to remain as steady in 1997, which is very important to the
upward trend of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Although Hong Kong's external trade grew only about five
percent for the first nine months of this year, it is expected to
have a considerable improvement in 1997 because of such favorable
factors as expected recovery in global demand and stronger import
 demand from China's inland areas.
</P>
<P>
The exports of services would benefit directly from the rebound
in external trade. The expected influx of tourists in the coming
year would further boost service exports including the hotel
sector.
</P>
<P>
In the first 10 months of this year, visitor arrivals rose by
15.9 percent, and the growth is expected to exceed 20 percent
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Inflation in 1997 is expected between 6.8 percent to 7.0
percent, slightly higher than this year's estimated 6.0 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
