<HEADLINE> State Media Urged to Help Promote Political Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh has urged the state-run media to promote the
country's political reform and national development, a local
newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit said that all branches of the state-run media,
including those under the military, will be fully utilized for
this goal, according to the "Bangkok Post".
</P>
<P>
Well-known academics and celebrities could educate the public
about political reform through panel discussions arranged on radio
and television, while other groups would also be allowed to use
the state media to voice their opinions, he said.
</P>
<P>
The state-run media will be made to present news in a
straightforward and accurate manner with the aim to educate people
and promote sound morals, the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
The state media can criticize the government's performance but
must adhere to the right principles in their reporting, for
instance, they should not rely solely on quotes from unnamed
sources when reporting on a controversial issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, other reports said that Chavalit earlier had
instructed related government agencies to strengthen their
information collection work to keep the government well-informed
on domestic and international situations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
