<HEADLINE> Greek President Starts Visit to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Greek President Costis
Stephanopoulos arrived in Egyptian Mediterranean port of
Alexandria today on a four-day visit to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Stephanopoulos will go on a sight-seeing tour of the
archaeological spots in the city and meet with the Greek community
there, before heading for Cairo later today. He is expected to
hold talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Talks are set to focus on vistas of bilateral economic ties,
the peace process in the Middle East and other issues of common
interest.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian-Greek summit will also cover the situation in the
Mediterranean and Egyptian-European Union economic partnership,
according to Foreign Ministry sources.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmad Goweli will hold talks with
the Greek delegation on enhancing trade exchange and removing
obstacles hampering Egyptian exports to the EU countries.
</P>
<P>
Greece comes seventh on the list of EU importing countries from
Egypt, Head of the Trade Representation Agency Esam Farrag, who is
also first deputy minister of trade and supply, told the Egyptian
Middle East News Agency Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Farrag added that bilateral trade balance tipped in favor of
Greece from 1993 to 1995. But it is now in Egypt's favor.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian exports to Greece include fresh fish, carpets, wool,
chemicals and iron and steel whereas the Greek exports to Egypt
include oil products, flour, vegetable oils and timber.
</P>
<P>
Trade and economic relations between Egypt and Greece were
booming since they signed an accord to encourage and protect
investments in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
