<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writers' Congress Closes, Ba Jin Resumes Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The Fifth National Congress of
the Chinese Writers' Association (CWA) closed here today, giving
Ba Jin a second term as president of the association.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen people, including Ma Feng, were elected
vice-presidents of the association.
</P>
<P>
The conference, held 12 years after the previous one, has drawn
great attention from Communist Party and government leaders and is
written into China's literary history as a significant event.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin delivered a speech at the opening
ceremony on December 16, affirming the country's achievements in
literature and expounding the glorious mission and guiding
principle of further flourishing China's socialist literature and
art.
</P>
<P>
During the five-day congress more than 800 representatives from
literary circles conducted widespread and in-depth discussions and
offered suggestions to prosper the country's literary creations.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of deliberations, the congress adopted the
Constitution of the Chinese Writers' Association, which makes
clearer the task of writers in the current situation.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday afternoon, a new leadership of the association was
elected, including a 180-member Fifth National Committee of the
CWA.
</P>
<P>
Some veteran writers who have made great contributions to
China's literature have been given honorary positions of the
CWA. Xie Bingxin was elected honorary president.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zilong, a newly elected vice-president, said at the
closing ceremony that the grand meeting posed both happiness and
great pressure for writers who take up the heavy responsibility of
opening a new chapter in China's literary history.
</P>
<P>
The congress has worked out a resolution calling on all writers
to go deeper into life, and work hard to produce more fine works.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
