<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Great Number of Bamboo, Wooden Slips Found in Hunan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of bamboo
and wooden slips dating back 1,700 years have been unearthed in
a downtown area of Changsha, capital of central China's Hunan
Province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists say that the slips, bearing at least
200,000 words, are the largest number of their kind ever found in
the country, and will contribute greatly to the study of the Three
Kingdoms Period (220-280).
</P>
<P>
The slips, found stored in a pit, are detailed records of the
political, economic, military, cultural and geographic situation
of Changsha prefecture, which was under the rule of the Wu State
(222-280).
</P>
<P>
The records cover taxes, renting, registration, legal system,
administration positions, rites, and storage.
</P>
<P>
Yu Weichao, curator of the prestigious National Museum of
Chinese History, says that find is as important as the discoveries
of the world-renowned oracle bones and shells from the Shang
Dynasty (16-11th Century BC) in central China's Henan Province and
the Dunhuang documents in the Mogao Grottos in northwest China's
Gansu Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
