<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Heads Home After Talks With Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
left for home following brief talks with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak this morning on the stagnant negotiations with Israel on
the Hebron issue.
</P>
<P>
Arafat briefed Mubarak on the outcome of his recent tour of
Europe, which took him to Austria, Albania, Italy and the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has just wound up his four-leg European tour which
started last Tuesday in a bid to scoop up support to the
Palestinians when negotiations with the Israelis are virtually
frozen at the present time.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's current visit to Cairo fell within constant
consultations between the two leaders on the Mideast peace
process, the Egyptian Middle East News Agency reported, giving no
more details about the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at dawn today, Arafat said that the Israeli
government has failed so far to implement any of the pending 34
articles in the Palestinian-Israeli Oslo II Agreement.
</P>
<P>
He specified some of the stumbling blocks as Israeli troop
redeployment in Hebron, the policy of sealing off areas to Arab
access, siege, confiscation of occupied lands, building
settlements and arrests.
</P>
<P>
Arafat showed his doubt that these problems would be solved
soon.
</P>
<P>
"There is no glimpse of hope for reaching in the future a
solution acceptable to the Palestinian party and realizing peace
in the region, in the light of such intransigence by the Israeli
government," he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinian Authority are expected to hold
talks to settle the sensitive issues such as the final status of
Palestinian territories including Jerusalem, Palestinian refugees
and border demarcation. The final status talks should be wrapped
up by May 1999 under the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
After two months of negotiations in vain, the two sides
renewed talks last Monday on Hebron, the last of the seven West
Bank towns from which Israel troops are supposed to redeploy
under the Oslo accords, but the talks were bogged down over
security arrangement for 400 Jews living among 100,000 Arabs in
the city.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the recent Israeli decision to grant financial
benefits to Jewish settlers in the occupied Arab lands to promote
settlement expansion has raised the ire of Palestinians, who said
the practice violated peace agreements and preempted final status
talks.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign peace treaty with the
Jewish state, has rejected the settlement policy as "illegal and
unacceptable" and blamed Israel for the "negative situation."
</P>
<P>
"Everybody is pessimistic about the future of the peace
process. This is not merely a French, Egyptian, Arab or European
impression, but an international impression," said Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa during his two-day visit to Paris
ending Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Summing up the stand of Egypt and the Arab world, Moussa said
"we won't accept peace with Israeli conditions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
