<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Sees Continued Economic Boom in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine economy will
continue to boom next year, with a sustained high growth of the
gross national product (GNP) and a remarkable drop in the
inflation rate, the National Economic and Development Authority
(NEDA) said today.
</P>
<P>
With short-term stabilization measures on track and most
structural adjustment measures firmed up, the GNP growth will
reach 7 to 8 percent in real terms in 1997, NEDA Director-General
Clelito Habito told reporters at an economic forum.
</P>
<P>
The projected GNP growth rate is a little higher than the 1996
target of 6.5 to 7.5 percent. During the first three quarters of
this year, the country registered a 7.1-percent GNP growth.
</P>
<P>
Habito, who is also socioeconomic planning secretary, said the
real GNP growth is expected to range between 7.1 and 7.8 percent,
a slight increase from the expected target of 6 to 6.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, inflation is expected to slow down significantly to
about 6.5 percent from the expected 8.5 percent this year. This
projection is closer to the norm of 4 to 5 percent among other
members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
Following the downward trend in inflation, the average domestic
interest rates are expected to also move downward in 1997, Habito
said.
</P>
<P>
The country's import liberalization as well as the tariff
reform program are both expected to support the competitiveness of
Philippine industries.
</P>
<P>
Barring adverse weather conditions, agriculture is expected to
perform better in 1997 given the government's additional budgetary
infusions for the construction of irrigation facilities and
post-harvest equipment.
</P>
<P>
On the fiscal side, the consolidated public sector financial
position, for the first time in two decades, is estimated to
balance in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Merchandise exports are projected to grow by 23.8 percent,
Habito said, adding that this growth will be supported by the
continued recovery of the Japanese, West European and U.S.
economies.
</P>
<P>
The attainment of the growth objectives in 1997 will hinge on
the achievement of stable prices, increased competitiveness of
Philippine products, structural adjustments, improved
infrastructure and continued political stability, Habito stressed.
</P>
<P>
To ensure sustained economic development in the medium term, he
added, the government needs to implement sound macroeconomic
policies for economic stability and long-run policies for
industrial restructuring and poverty alleviation and human
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Pest Management Program Gains Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's integrated pest
management (IPM) program gained much success with the area of rice
crops using the method increasing to more than one million
hectares, the ministry of agriculture and rural development said.
</P>
<P>
Millions of farmers in the northern and southern deltas as well
as in the highland areas have been taught the IPM knowledge, the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The IPM is an inter-state program launched by the UN Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) in the 1980s, aimed at increasing
the output of rice crops and protecting the environment by helping
rice-growing countries in South and Southeast Asia raise the
effectiveness of pest control and curb the use of insecticide.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam joined the IPM program in early 1990 when the program
entered its second phase.
</P>
<P>
The IPM program is significant to Vietnam where more than 80
percent of the population subsists on agriculture and more than
six million hectares are earmarked for rice crops every
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Economic Slowdown, of Cyclical Nature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Although the year 1996 has
seen the economic growth of Singapore slowing down from 11.4
percent in the first quarter to 3.2 percent in the third quarter,
the Singapore Government and economists here believe the slowdown
is only of cyclical nature and the economy is expected to pick up
by the middle of 1997.
</P>
<P>
After enjoying 14 straight quarters of over seven percent
growth, the Singapore economy suddenly started to slow down from
the second quarter this year. In just nine months, the quarterly
economic growth fell from 11.4 percent in the first three months
of the year to 3.2 percent in the third quarter, marking the
lowest quarterly growth level in the past ten years since the
economic recession in the middle of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The government was therefore forced to revise its economic
growth forecast for the whole year downwards from the initial
7.5-8.5 percent to 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Economists here attributed the slowdown to an unfortunate
confluence of several negative forces, with the biggest being the
global cyclical electronics slump, while a sluggish stock market,
a policy-induced property cooling-down, and the structural
weaknesses in several sectors at home also contributing to the
overall slowdown.
</P>
<P>
The electronics industry, like in the whole region, has been
the driving force behind Singapore's robust growth in recent
years. It accounts for, by some estimates, around 70 percent of
Singapore's non-oil domestic exports, 44 percent of manufacturing
value-added, and 14 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Therefore, unsurprisingly, a global electronics inventory
overhang that surfaced late last year showed up in Singapore some
six months later in June, resulting in the first dip in exports in
four years. Exports then continued to contract in August and
September, leading to the industrial output decline in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
The 4.3 percent contraction in the industry, its worst
performance in a decade, also had its unfortunate impact felt in a
number of other sectors. For one, the global electronics downturn
had also hit regional economies such as Malaysia and Thailand. And
this, in turn, had led to knock-on effects on Singapore's major
services like shipping and entrepot trade.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts pointed out that it was not electronics alone
that led to Singapore's less-than-sparkling economic performance.
The marine industry, for example, continued to be affected by
weakness in the global industry, and the petroleum products and
petrochemicals industries were hit by both maintenance shutdowns
and keen competition.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the electrical appliances industry continued to be
affected by relocation and weaker demand, while growth in the
financial services sub-sector, pulled down by a lackluster bourse,
reported a mere 3.3 percent growth, the lowest in seven quarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
