<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 20 (Xinhua) -- More than 700 exotic lizards
and snakes are to be set free in Zimbabwe's bushes.
</P>
<P>
The exotic lizards and snakes, worth 100,000 US Dollars, were
impounded by Pretoria authorities last month under the Animals
Protection Act while being smuggled from Mozambique to the United
States, where there is a lucrative market for them.
</P>
<P>
The reptiles automatically became South African property and a
decision was taken by the Pretoria government to have some of them
set free in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Arrangements for the exercise have been made by the local
department of national parks and wildlife management and the
Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals (SPCA).
</P>
<P>
Inspector Neil Fraser of the South African SPCA told the Zimbabwe
National News Agency in Harare on Thursday a total of 23 puff adders
and 609 lizards were to be set free in northeastern zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
He said some of the reptiles had to be released in Zimbabwe
because it had a sound wildlife conservation policy similar to South
Africa's. enditem

