<HEADLINE> West, Central Africa Records Higher Maize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 20 (Xinhua) -- There has been a phenomenal increase
in maize production in west and central Africa in recent years, the
International Institute of Tropical Agriculture (IITA) based in
Ibadan, Nigeria, said in its 1995 annual report.
</P>
<P>
The newly released report said the average annual growth rate
of maize production in the region for the 1983-92 is 4.1 percent,
whereas the percentage for east and southern Africa in the same
period is only 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
It said that Burkina Faso, Ghana, Guinea and Mali recorded
extremely high annual growth rates and the land area devoted to
maize production has increased at an average rate of 2.7 percent
a year in the period.
</P>
<P>
The report attributes the growth in production to the introduction
of high-yielding, drought-tolerant, early and extra-early maturity
varieities.
</P>
<P>
The new varieties have a yield potential of five tonnes per
hectare, and are ready for harvest as green maize in 60 days, or as
dry grains in 75 to 80 days, compared with 120 days for older
varieties, the report said. enditem

=12201041

=12201041
