<HEADLINE> Lebanon Refuses Israel's Proposal of Arab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Elias
Hrawi has rejected an Israeli proposal to deploy Arab
peacekeeping forces in south Lebanon, and accused Israel of
igniting border violence to scare away foreign investments
pledged in Washington earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
The president's remarks came as tensions escalated in south
Lebanon amid repeated Israeli air strikes at suspected guerrilla
targets on hills opposite the Israeli self-styled "security
zone" in the area.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli proposal for the deployment of Jordanian and
Egyptian forces in the south is an attempt to drive a wedge
between Lebanon and Syria," Hrawi was quoted by today's Daily
Star, Beirut's only English daily, as saying
</P>
<P>
The head of state made the speech to a number of parliament
members who visited him at the Beirut Presidential Palace
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Israeli Public Security Minister Avigdor
Kahalani suggested that a multinational peacekeeping force that
includes Egyptian and Jordanian contingents be deployed in the
occupied border enclave in south Lebanon after Israel's troop
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Israel established the 1,100-square-kilometer "security zone"
in south Lebanon in 1985 as a buffer to guard against
cross-boarder guerrilla attacks on its northern Jewish
settlements.
</P>
<P>
Both Egypt and Jordan are bound to the Jewish state by peace
treaties, and Kahalani's exclusion of Damascus was perceived
here as an attempt to undercut Syria's role, the newspaper
noted.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi said should Israel agree to withdraw from the so-called
"security zone," the Lebanese army and Lebanese security forces
"are fully capable of maintaining peace and protecting the
border. We do not need to bring in Arab forces."
</P>
<P>
He said Israel was trying to undermine the success achieved
at the Friends of Lebanon conference, which was held in
Washington last Monday, by fueling tension in south Lebanon to
scare international investors.
</P>
<P>
During the Washington conference, 29 countries and eight
international financial institutions promised to provide 3.2
billion U.S. dollars in aid to help Lebanon execute its ambitious
reconstruction plans in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
"The forum in Washington considerably bolstered the morale of
the Lebanese," Hrawi said, "Israel is trying to undermine the
psychological and material gains we received at the conference."
</P>
<P>
He said the only way to counter Israeli schemes against
Lebanon was for the participants in the Washington forum to
expedite the grants and loans quickly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
