<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The Italian comedian Marcello Mastroianni died of cancer
Thursday morning in Paris at the age of 72. Mastroianni, to be
buried in Italy, starred in such milestone movies as "We Loved
Each Other So Much," "La Dolce Vita," "Eight and a Half," and "The
City of Women."
</P>
<P>
-- Some 23 members of the Peruvian guerrilla group Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary Movement were still holding about 500 hostages at the
residence of the Japanese ambassador in Lima. Difficult
negotiations was going on between the guerrillas and the Peruvian
government, while the International Red Cross was sending food and
other daily necessities to the hostages.
</P>
<P>
-- France has abandoned its hope of obtaining the seat of the
Naples-based NATO South Command after NATO defense ministers held
talks in Brussels on November 17-18. However, Paris is insisting
on take-over of the seat by a European general. A British admiral
is the most possible candidate for the seat.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The morale of French employers is a little bit higher at the
end of 1996 than one year ago, shows an annual poll by Le Figaro.
About 30 percent of the bosses in France are optimistic about
1997, against last year's 27 percent; and 42 percent of them
expect a revenue growth of zero to one percent next year, while 60
percent expect to maintain their present number of employees next
year.
</P>
<P>
-- The case around the discovery last week in a Paris shopping
center of a bag containing a gas bottle and nails -- the
ingredients for the bomb used in the attack on a Paris train early
this month -- turned into a thriller story Thursday morning. One
of the key witnesses, a shop-keeper, was abducted for several
hours before being released by the kidnappers, who wanted to know
what he had told the police. The shop-keeper reportedly saw three
North Africans placing the gas bottle in the shopping center
before running away.  
</P>
</TEXT>
