<HEADLINE> S. African Air Force to Upgrade Transport Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Johannesburg, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The South Africn Air Force
(SAAF) will spend 500 million Rand (about 108 million U.S. dollars) to
upgrade its 33-year-old fleet of 12 Lockheed C-130 transport aircraft,
the local newspaper the Star reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
This is the largest order placed by the SAAF since international
military sanctions agatinst South Africa were lifted in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The five-year program will be carried out in Britain and South
Africa, Acting Chief of the SAAF Bertus Burger was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Of all the 12 C-130 transport aircraft, five were newly
presented as gifts by the United States on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing at a ceremony at which the United States Air Force
handed over the gifts of the first two of five C-130s to the SAAF,
Berger said "by world standards, upgrading aircraft which have had
33-years of service is fairly late, but to pay 500 million Rand for
such an upgrade program is much less expensive than the cost of
purchasing new aircraft."
</P>
<P>
The upgrade plan, he said, would be undertaken as part of a joint
venture between Britan's Marshall company and Denel Aviaton, a
subsidiary of the Denel Group. Three of the planes are to be upgraded
in Brtain and the remainder in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Charge'd Affaires Bob Pringle, who also attended the aircraft
handover ceremony, said that his country's gift to the SAAF
symbolized the American desire for strong links with South Africa. He
said "through this kind of cooperation, the U.S. and South Africa are
working together to improve the SAAF's ability to respond to the needs
of South Africa as well as the southern African region."
</P>
<P>
The remianing three C-130s transport planes are due to reach
Waterkloof Air Force base before mid 1997, the report said. enditem

