<HEADLINE> Arafat Pessimistic About Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
today expressed his disappointment about the pace of the stalled
peace talks due to Israel's hardline policy, saying that a quick
solution to all differences would be impossible.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority president arrived here at
dawn today for talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said upon arrival that the Israeli government has failed
so far to implement any of the pending 34 articles in the
Palestinian-Israeli Oslo II Agreement.
</P>
<P>
He specified some of the stumbling blocks as Israeli troops
redeployment in Hebron, the policy of sealing off areas to Arab
access, siege, confiscation of occupied lands, building
settlements and arrests.
</P>
<P>
Arafat showed his doubt that these problems would be solved
soon.
</P>
<P>
"There is no glimpse of hope for reaching in the future a
solution acceptable to the Palestinian party and realizing peace
in the region, in the light of such intransigence by the Israeli
government," he said.
</P>
<P>
After two months of negotiations in vain, the two sides renewed
talks last Monday on Hebron, the last of the seven West Bank towns
from which Israel troops are supposed to redeploy under the Oslo
accords, but the talks were bogged down over security arrangement
for 400 Jews living among 100,000 Arabs in the city.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the recent Israeli decision to grant financial
benefits to Jewish settlers in the occupied Arab lands to promote
settlement expansion has raised the ire of Palestinians, who said
the practice violated peace agreements and preempted final status
talks.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign peace treaty with the
Jewish state, has rejected the settlement policy as "illegal and
unacceptable" and blamed the "negative situation" on Israel.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody is pessimistic about the future of the peace
process. This is not merely a French, Egyptian, Arab or European
impresson, but an international impression," said Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr during his visit to Paris Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival, Arafat said that he will brief Mubarak on the
outcome of his recent tour of Europe, which took him to Austria,
Albania, Italy and the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
He said he will seek the Egyptian president's advice especially
when negotiations with the Israelis are virtually frozen at the
present time.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has just winded up his four-leg European tour which
started last Tuesday in a bid to drum up stronger support to the
Palestinians and the Mideast peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 08:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel May Accept a Limited Palestinian State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 20 (Xinhua) -- In a sign of rare
flexibility, a senior Israeli official indicated today that
Israel may accept a Palestinian state with strictly defined and
limited sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, media adviser to Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu, said in an interview with The Jerusalem Post that this
was because the partition between the two sides already existed
and the notion of "Greater Israel" was no longer possible.
</P>
<P>
"I think partition is a fact. The question now is really what
sort of partition," said Bar-Illan, who is often described as the
leading ideological aide to Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
He said that a Palestinian state already existed to some
extent. "In many ways, it is a state ... In many ways, it is much
more of a state than it was envisioned in the Oslo agreement," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Bar-Illan said the Likud government would insist on limiting
its sovereignty, such as demanding its demilitarization.
</P>
<P>
He said there was no great difference today between the Likud
and Labor, due to Likud's adherence to Oslo accords. But he
criticized the previous Labor government for no forcing Arafat to
stick to limits which, if unchecked, would lead to a militarized
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
"I think when the Labor Party talked about the state, they
said that they wanted it to be demilitarized; but if it isn't,
well there is nothing much we can do about it," he said.
</P>
<P>
"While Netanyahu is making it a condition for the existence of
an entity, whether you call it a state or not is not really the
important thing. The condition is that it cannot have unlimited
sovereignty," he continued.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that if the Palestinians declared statehood at
some point in the future, he believed that "the whole world will
recognize it."
</P>
<P>
Talking about Netanyahu's ideology, Bar-Illan said, " I think
in general he is no longer (in favor of ) a whole-land-of Israel
movement. I don't think he feels that there is any chance of the
land of Israel remaining completely under the exclusive rule of
Israel."
</P>
<P>
On the issue of settlement expansion, Bar-Illan repeated the
government declaration that while construction within existing
settlements would continue, no "another square inch" would be
added to any settlement.
</P>
<P>
He asked the Palestinians not to worry that Israel was seeking
to preclude the negotiations on the final disposition of the
territories, a criticism made even by U.S. President Bill Clinton
early this week.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinian Authority (PA) are expected to hold
final-status talks to settle the sensitive issues such as the
final status of Palestinian territories including Jerusalem,
Palestinian refugees and border demarcation.
</P>
<P>
The PA is demanding the establishment of an independent state
with eastern Jerusalem as its capital, but Israel's Likud
government has declared its opposition to such a state. The issue
has to be resolved in the final-status talks, which should be
wrapped up by May 1999 under the Oslo accords. 
</P>
</TEXT>
