<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israel-U.S. Binational Research and
Development Foundation has recently approved an $11 million
investment as its 50 percent cost-share in 16 new projects
between U.S. and Israeli high-tech companies, reported The
Jerusalem Post Friday.
</P>
<P>
The projects are in all areas of technology but communications
accounts for 30 percent and medical for 20 percent. The American
partners include Siemens Medical, Packard Bell and SmithKline
Beecham.
</P>
<P>
Projects previously approved by the foundation yielded $338
million in direct sales in 1996.
</P>
<P>
-- Net-Scene, an Israeli high-tech firm in Herzliya, north of
Tel Aviv, has announced the release of its virtual seminar
Internet software especially designed to help drivers improve
their behavior on the road.
</P>
<P>
Geared for companies that employ many drivers, such as bus and
trucking companies, the technology provides employers with a way
to educate their staff.
</P>
<P>
-- RADVision, a member of the Tel Aviv-based RAD group, has
announced the development of a full range of H.323 products that
will enable videoconferencing vendors and system integrators to
adopt and offer videoconferencing solutions to users.
</P>
<P>
-- SanDisk Corporation, the world's leading supplier of flash
data storage products, has announced that it will establish a
design center in Israel which will go into operation on December
24.
</P>
<P>
The center, which will be staffed by six design engineers,
will utilize SanDisk flash semiconductor technology to design
flash storage cards.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Electricity and Energy Maher
Abaza said Thursday that the power linkage grid for Maghreb
countries will be completed and operated in 1998.
</P>
<P>
He expected a great economic return for Arab-Maghreb countries
as a result of this project particularly after Spain and Italy
agreed to participate in it.
</P>
<P>
-- Egypt is undertaking an ambitious plan to expand the use of
natual gas as fuel for cars, announced Thursday by Petroleum
Minister Hamdi Al--Banbi, who opened the first station to supply
cars with natural gas in Alexanderia.
</P>
<P>
Agreement was reached by his ministry and Nasser Bank to
provide easy loans to enable car owners to convert to the use of
natural gas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
