<HEADLINE> ADB Resident Mission in Vietnam Starts Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank's
(ADB) resident mission in Vietnam was launched here Thursday,
according to the State Bank of Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
ADB resident representative Jean-Pierre Verbiest assumed office
in the largest recipient country of the bank's zero interest loans
which carry a service charge of one percent per annum and long
maturities.
</P>
<P>
The ADB Board of Directors approved the establishment of the
mission earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Since resuming assistance to Vietnam in 1993, the bank has
approved 13 loans totalling 937.5 million U.S. dollars and 53
technical assistance grants amounting to 36.9 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Over the next three years, ADB's lending to Vietnam is expected
to range between 300-350 million dollars per year at concessional
terms.
</P>
<P>
An additional 30 million dollars is expected to be provided in
the form of technical assistance over the same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
