<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Software Industry Rises by 61 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 20 (Xinhua) -- India's software industry
grew by a record 61.7 percent in the first six months of the
financial year 1996-97 ending March 31 compared with the
corresponding period in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
According to a latest survey conducted by the National
Association of Software and Service Companies (NASSCOM), the
domestic software market grew by 62 percent and the software
export industry 61.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
In absolute terms, the industry generated an estimated revenue
of 30.9 billion rupees (870.42 million US dollars) during the
period.
</P>
<P>
The phenomenal growth of 62 percent in the domestic software
market was due to lower import duties on software and the success
of an anti-piracy campaign in the country, NASSCOM executive
director Dewang Mehta said.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the export growth to increases in offshore
services and new initiatives of Indian software exports to the
United States, Europe, Australia and South Africa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
