<HEADLINE> 12 Policemen Held on Murder Charge in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 20 (Xinhua) -- A senior superintendent of
police and 11 other police officers yesterday appeared in a
Nairobi court charged with the murder of two Kenyatta University
students on Wednesday, the Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The two students were shot dead by police while mourning their
colleague who was killed by police at Egerton University in
Njoro, about 190 kilometers northwest of Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
All the 12 were unrepresented while the prosecution was led by
superintendent Christopher Opondo.
</P>
<P>
The accused policemen appeared before Chief Magistrate
Pamellah Uniter Kidullah, and all of them requested to be
remanded in police custody in order to make certain arrangements
for their families after the charges were read to them.
</P>
<P>
But Opondo opposed the application by the policemen to have
them remanded in police custody "due to the seriousness of the
charge they face."
</P>
<P>
The case will be mentioned on January 2 next year.
</P>
<P>
Kenyans yesterday reacted angrily over the police killing of
three university students on their campuses on Tuesday and
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Catholic Church, parents and a cross-section of leaders
demanded the immediate sacking of the commissioner of police.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement, 25 legislators from the ruling party and
the opposition asked for the restructuring of the Ministry
for Education, the public university administrations and the
Police Forces to restore public confidence in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
