<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Provisional Legislators to Be Elected Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The Provisional Legislative
Council (PLC) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) will be elected by the Selection Committee for the First
Government of the HKSAR at its fourth plenary session in Shenzhen,
southern China, Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 60 provisional legislators will be chosen from among the
130 candidates by the 400 members of the Selection Committee at
the session to be presided over by the chairman and vice-chairmen
of the Preparatory Committee for the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The PLC in fact is the product of the British side's unilateral
act to push through the "Constitutional Package" which destroyed
the "through train" for Hong Kong's existing Legislative Council
as agreed upon by the Chinese and British governments.
</P>
<P>
To avoid the legal vacuum in the transition period and to
ensure effective functioning of the HKSAR, the Preparatory
Committee made a decision to establish the PLC at its second
session held in Beijing in March this year in line with the Basic
Law and related decisions of China's National People's Congress
(NPC).
</P>
<P>
The Preparatory Committee also laid down the tasks for the PLC
and decided that the operation of the PLC cannot be extended
beyond June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
On October 6, the Sixth Plenary Session of the Preparatory
Committee approved the methods for the formation of the PLC of
HKSAR, which stipulated that the Selection Committee will elect
the members of the PLC through secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
From November 18 to December 9, the nomination of applicants
for the PLC members were conducted in Hong Kong. A total of 134
application forms had been completed by the deadline.
</P>
<P>
Applicants came from various sectors in Hong Kong, including
accountants, lawyers, bankers, teachers, doctors, artists,
entrepreneurs, businessmen and labor representatives.
</P>
<P>
The Seventh Plenary Session of the Preparatory Committee held
in Shenzhen on December 12 confirmed 130 candidates for the PLC,
including 34 members of the current Hong Kong Legislature.
</P>
<P>
In the past week, the candidates held a series of activities,
writing articles in newspapers and meeting with communities, to
convey their political visions.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all candidates expressed their readiness to contribute
to Hong Kong's smooth transition and play an active role in
legislation to ensure Hong Kong's long-term prosperity and
stability.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that some 200 reporters from Hong Kong and
overseas will cover the fourth session of the Selection Committee
in Shenzhen Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The venue was originally planned at Hong Kong, but the British
side's refusal to cooperate forced the meeting to move to
Shenzhen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fierce Fighting Rages in Southwestern Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting raged yesterday
between Ugandan government army and the rebels of the Allied
Democratic Force (ADF) in the Rwenzori mountains, southwestern
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
According to the local daily ''the New Vision'' today, an
estimated 2,000 government soldiers pursued the rebels believed
to be over 800, who attacked villages in the mountainous area.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the number of the casualties on both sides was not
known due to a new order barring field commanders from talking to
the press.
</P>
<P>
The fighting sparked off a fresh displacement of thousands of
people, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
At least 3,000 civilians were said to be on the move from
the mountain area to the lower area.
</P>
<P>
After Zairean troops lost Beni, Kasindi and other towns in the
eastern Zaire, the ADF rebels broke off and entered into Uganda,
the paper said. enditem

=12200818

=12200818
NNNN
16:21 16:21 g # PAB
</P>
