<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Agriculture Develops Fast in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Agriculture in Uganda has been
recovering and developing fast in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture is the most important sector in Uganda's economy.
Agricultural output value accounts for 51 percent of its gross
domestic product and 95 percent of its export earning. Now,
Uganda is one of the nine African countries self-sufficient in
grain.
</P>
<P>
Coffee growing as the pillar of the country's national economy
has in recent years recovered and developed very rapidly. Its
production has increased steadily from 92,000 tons in 1992 to
180,000 tons this year. Uganda ranks second after Cote d'Ivoire
in Africa in coffee production.
</P>
<P>
The value of coffee exports of Uganda accounts for 75 percent
of the country's total export income.
</P>
<P>
The recovery and development of coffee production in Uganda
are attributed to the steps taken by the government. These
include cancelling monopoly of coffee exports by the Coffee
Marketing Board, encouraging private companies to export coffee
and privatising coffee nurseries to speed up the replacement of
low-yielding coffee trees.
</P>
<P>
Cotton was Uganda's main export after coffee in the 1950s and
1960s. But cotton production plummeted in the 1970s and early
1980s, because of political turmoil and civil war. The country's
cotton production fell to almost zero in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985, the country's cotton production increased
gradually, to 27,000 bales in 1989 and further to 60,000 bales in
1993. In the 1995/96 season, the country is expected to export
69,000 bales, 1.28 times that of the previous season.
</P>
<P>
The above situation is attributed to measures taken by the
government. It has considered the revival of cotton production as
a strategy for poverty reduction in the country, because cotton
growing is a major income earning activity for many Ugandan
peasants, particularly in the poverty-stricken northeast of the
country.
</P>
<P>
One of the major measures for the increase of cotton
production is the introduction of a prolific cotton variety,
which yields twice as much as that of traditional varieties.
</P>
<P>
Another measure is to abolish the Cotton Marketing Board's
monopoly over cotton export and the monopoly by the cooperative
unions over ginning. As a result, production enthusiasm of cotton
farmers has been increased.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
