<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Agriculture Develops Fast in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Tea was Uganda's fourth
foreign exchange earner after coffee, cotton and tourism in the
late 1960s and 1970s. At present, it has become the third, after
coffee and tourism.
</P>
<P>
In 1972, Uganda's tea output reached 23 million kilograms.
However, in August that year, all ethnic Asians who controlled
over 70 percent of the industry in the country were expelled by
the Amin administration. The tea plantations were then so badly
managed that only less than 10 percent of the estates had been
under cultivation by 1986, when the tea output dropped to only
one million kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987, the government has taken measures to recover the
industry. These are to return tea estates to Asians, abolish
state monopoly of tea export and privatize four tea factories in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Due to the measures, tea output in the country had increased
from 1.5 million kilos in 1981 to close 12.7 million kilos in
1995. In the same period, tea exports increased from 0.5 million
kilos to some 10.7 million kilos. It is estimated that by the end
of this century, tea industry in Uganda, the world's 10th largest
tea producer, will be fully recovered.
</P>
<P>
At present, tobacco is the fourth most important export crop
in Uganda after coffee, tea and cotton. The country's tobacco
industry has made a tremendous progress in recent years too.
Tobacco leaf production had increased from 1,963 tons in 1984 to
6,638 tons in l995.
</P>
<P>
The progrss is attributed to the formation of a multi-national
company in 1984 with the British American Tobacco owning 70
percent of the shares and the Ugandan government 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
The company, which holds the monopoly of the industry, has
injected a large amount of fund into the leaf-growing areas to
rehabilitate the infrastructure and farms destroyed during the
civil war in the 1970s and early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
In order to reduce dependence of the country's economy on
coffee exportation, an export diversification program has been
carried out in the country. Vanilla production is the best sector
in carrying out the program. According to statistics from the
Finance Ministry, the output of vanilla green beans had increased
from 5,400 kilos in 1990 to 37,866 kilos in 1993, while export
value of the crop from 43,250 US Dollars to 437,366 Dollars in
the same period.
</P>
<P>
Grain production in the country has also been recovering and
developing fast in recent years. Output of banana, one of the
major staple food for Ugandans, had increased from 7.76 million
tons in 1988 to 8.5 million tons in 1995. Uganda now is the
largest banana producer in the world.
</P>
<P>
The output of sweet potatoes had increased from 1.65 million
tons in 1989 to 1.8 million tons in 1995, ranking the country
first in Africa and fourth in the world.
</P>
<P>
The grain production situation is due to national
reconciliation and economic reform policies carried out by the
governmnent in the past 11 years. It is these policies that most
peaceful and stable political situation has appeared in the most
parts of the country since 1986. 
</P>
</TEXT>
