<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tasks for HKSAR Provisional Legislative Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The Provisional Legislative
Council of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) to
be elected  Saturday is charged with seven major tasks.
</P>
<P>
According to the March 1996 decision on the establishment of
the Provisional Legislative Council made by the Preparatory
Committee for the HKSAR of China's National People's Congress
(NPC), the Provisional Legislative Council has the following
tasks:
</P>
<P>
1. According to the stipulations of the Basic Law of the HKSAR,
the council is to be responsible for enacting indispensable laws
for the normal operation of the HKSAR, and revising and abrogating
laws if necessary;
</P>
<P>
2. It is to examine and approve the budget submitted by the
HKSAR government;
</P>
<P>
3. It is to approve taxation and public expenditure;
</P>
<P>
4. It is to debate on the policy address delivered by the Chief
Executive;
</P>
<P>
5. It is to approve the appointment of the judges of the HKSAR
Court of Final Appeal and the Chief Judge of the High Court;
</P>
<P>
6. The chairman of the council will participate in naming the
six Hong Kong members of the HKSAR Basic Law Committee under the
NPC Standing Committee; and
</P>
<P>
7. The council is to handle all the necessary matters which are
to be dealt with before the establishment of the First Legislative
Council of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The decision said that the laws approved by the council before
July 1, 1997, will go into effect from the day of the
establishment of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The council will continue working until the first Legislative
Council of the HKSAR is founded, and the deadline is set on June
30, 1998, the decision said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
