<HEADLINE> Candidates for Provisional Legislature Vow to Do Good </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Most of the 130 candidates
for the 60-member Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) have made public
their ideas and visions in newspapers or meetings over the past
week.
</P>
<P>
They explained why they run for the PLC and spoke of the
priorities in legislation, but they all pledged to do good to Hong
Kong once they are elected.
</P>
<P>
Former legislator Tam Wai-chu said that she decided to run for
the PLC because she wanted to continue to pave the way for Hong
Kong's handover. "I want to work together with the 6.3 million
Hong Kong people to implement the principle of 'One country, Two
systems'."
</P>
<P>
Surveyor Leung Chun-ying, who is also a vice chairman of the
Preparatory Committee for the First Government of the HKSAR, said
that the establishment of the PLC is another important stage for
the establishment of the HKSAR government, and it is also a
significant measure to ensure that the HKSAR government can
operate effectively and legally.
</P>
<P>
He said that there is one simple and important purpose for him
to participate in the election, that is, to carry out the tasks
laid down by the Preparatory Committee.
</P>
<P>
Lawyer Wong Ying-ho said if he is elected, he will suggest the
PLC give priority to laws that will promote economic development
and people's livelihood. As for public expenditure, he hopes a
balanced budget will be drafted to protect the interests of
different levels and make good use of limited resources.
</P>
<P>
Incumbent legislator Ip Kwok-him said, being locally born and
bred, he should make his part of contribution to Hong Kong at this
historical turning point. He hoped to join the PLC and serve the
HKSAR government with his legislative experience.
</P>
<P>
An overwhelming majority of the candidates have explained their
ideas to members of the Selection Committee who are to choose the
60 provisional legislators through secret balloting Saturday in
Shenzhen, southern China.
</P>
<P>
They have also explained to the public what they will do if
they are elected. Some of them stress issues such as education,
culture, economic development and environment protection, and some
give priority to women's rights, social welfare, housing, medical
and health work.
</P>
<P>
The candidates come from a wide spectrum of society,
representing people at different levels and in different sectors.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
