<HEADLINE> India, Malaysia to Enhance Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 20 (Xinhua) -- India and Malaysia are
expected to sign an agreement today to set up a joint venture to
develop India's first private port in Gujarat state, southern
India.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamed, who arrived here
Thursday on a three-day official visit, will attend the signing
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Another joint venture to be set up is between the Malaysian
firm P.K. Technology and an Indian computer software company in
Bangalore, capital of Karnataka state, official sources said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir came here to receive the Jawaharlal Nehru Award for
International Understanding for his contribution to building
closer cooperation amongst developing nations. The award carries
a citation, a trophy and a cash component of 1.5 million rupees
(42,254 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Mahathir will hold talks with Indian President S.D. Sharma and
Prime Minister Deve Gowda on bilateral relations as well as
regional and international issues of mutual interest.
</P>
<P>
Both Malaysia and India are keen to enhance their economic and
trade ties. The joint venture on the private port in Gujarat is
only the first in a number of projects involving power generation,
telecommunications, ports, electronics, roads and highways.
</P>
</TEXT>
