<HEADLINE> Earnings from Overseas Tourism to Top 10 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Overseas tourists will have
poured a record 10 billion US dollars into China during 1996,
tourism officials have reported.
</P>
<P>
The officials describe the growing tourism levels as an
exciting time for China.
</P>
<P>
The information was disclosed today by Sun Gang, deputy
director of the China National Tourism Administration, who is
especially in Shanghai to attend the '96 Domestic Tourism Fair.
</P>
<P>
China is also reported to have received more domestic tourists
during 1996, contributing 160 billion yuan (one U.S. dollars
equals to about 8.3 Chinese yuan) to the country's earnings from
tourism services.
</P>
<P>
Last year China received 46.4 million overseas tourists, and
earned 8.7 billion U.S. dollars from tourist related services, both
showing marked increases compared with corresponding figures of
1990.
</P>
<P>
Between 1991 and 1995, the country received 203 million overseas
tourists and earned 27.5 billion U.S. dollars from tourism.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the fair attributed the success in tourism
sector to China's policy which encourages various organizations at
different levels to develop tourism industries vigorously if
conditions allow, and to the improve basic facilities across the
country.
</P>
<P>
China has built 1,400 scenic spots each capable of receiving
hundreds of overseas tourists annually, and has more than 3,000
hotels authorized to receive overseas tourists, providing 450,000
guest rooms.
</P>
<P>
The China National Tourism Administration has been working hard
to adjust the structure of tourism programs, including the
establishment of 12 state-level tourism and holiday zones, in
addition to efforts made to continue to improve tourism services
both for domestic and overseas tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
