<HEADLINE> Retired Brig, Four Others Summoned in Espionage Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 20 (Xinhua) -- A Delhi court has summoned a
retired brigadier, a former union government adviser in the
Department of Electronics and three others for their alleged role
in a nine-year-old espionage case, local newspapers reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The case involves smuggling of the country's top secret radar
and helicopter technology to France and the Netherlands, the
newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
Acting upon a complaint by the Central Bureau of Investigation
(CBI), Chief Metropolitan Magistrate Prem Kumar on Thursday
ordered the five to appear in court on January 30 next year to
stand trial for offenses "prejudicial to the country's security
and integrity."
</P>
<P>
Among the accused are retired Brigadier Rajpal Singh, former
union government adviser Narayan Waman Nerurkar and owner of a
chain of private firms in Delhi Krishna Kumar Jajodia.
</P>
<P>
The espionage bid fell through after a courier company official
found the documents Jajodia gave him to be secret defense papers
and reported to his bosses who then lodged a complaint with the
CBI.
</P>
<P>
The documents included an 86-page photocopy of a report on
surveillance radar and a 13-page typed draft letter addressed to
the Defense Ministry dealing with the subjects like tactical
control radar systems.
</P>
<P>
The CBI had also seized a note on utility helicopters for the
army from Jajodia's home in south Delhi.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
