<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Political Orientation Should Be Closely Watched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 20 (Xinhua) -- As Japan sought to play a larger
role in the international community in 1996, its domestic politics
continued its drift to the right, prompting fears among
neighboring Asian nations of a revival of the Japanese militarism.
</P>
<P>
The year 1996 saw Tokyo whipping up public sentiment for a
re-drawing of the Japan-U.S. security pact, a move aimed at
expanding the scope and remit of Japan's defense forces, to
include joint operations in any regional crises.
</P>
<P>
Along with strengthening the Japanese-U.S. alliance, Japan has
in recent years continually increased military expenditure and
tried to promote its political influence by sending troops abroad.
</P>
<P>
In its annual white paper on defense, Tokyo wantonly plays up
the "China threat" theory, calling for a guard against
defense-oriented military moves by China.
</P>
<P>
On July 29, Ryutaro Hashimoto became the first prime minister
since 1985 to pay homage to the notorious Tokyo-based Yasukuni
Shrine housing tablets of 14 class-A war criminals, including
wartime prime minister Hideki Tojo.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, accompanied by seven cabinet members, visited the
shrine in an official capacity, undermining the significance of a
statement by then Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama on August 15,
1995, to mark the 50th anniversary of the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Murayama expressed remorse over Japan's
aggression and colonial rule of other Asian states before and
during the war and resolved not to repeat the "mistake".
</P>
<P>
The shrine has generated fear abroad and parochial nationalism
and patriotism at home. For it is really a political institution
rather than a religious shrine.
</P>
<P>
Although some politicians in Japan acknowledge the country's
past atrocities which brought great suffering to neighboring Asian
countries, the political community in Japan overall has done no
soul-searching over the country's aggression during the first half
of the century.
</P>
<P>
Some leading politicians have attempted to whitewash Japan's
wartime atrocities by covering up historical facts, leading most
Japanese young people to the sole knowledge of the atomic bombing
of their own country and giving them none or a very shallow
knowledge of the disaster Japan inflicted on China and other Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
These politicians even demanded China "correct" its textbooks
on the Nanjing Massacre, also known as the Rape of Nanking, in
which more than 300,000 innocent Chinese were killed by Japanese
invaders in December 1937.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto's ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) issued a
15-point platform before the October general election, which
included support for the LDP ministers' visit to the Yasukuni
Shrine and for territorial claims over China's Diaoyu islands in
the East China Sea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Political Stability Vital to Developing Nations: Chinese Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries will find
it impossible to boost their economies or raise people's living
standard without a stable political environment, Chinese Premier
Li Peng said today.
</P>
<P>
Li made the statement in Beijing during a meeting with visiting
Togolese Minister for Foreign Affairs and Cooperation Koffi Panou.
</P>
<P>
Expressing satisfaction over the sustained, healthy development
of Sino-Togo ties, the premier said there has been a good momentum
in bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He made special mention of President Eyadema's fourth
successful visit to China last year, saying it had ushered
bilateral ties to a new level.
</P>
<P>
Li praised the Togolese government and people for the
remarkable achievements made in safeguarding national political
stability and restoring the economy. The moves had been made in
order to pursue a political system and path for development
suiting Togo's own national situation, Li said, adding that China
respects the choice made by the Togolese people.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Li also spoke highly of the Togolese
government's "one China" stand, forging no official ties of any
kind with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Panou said China has achieved great success in domestic
construction and in its performance on the international stage.
According to Panou, China has always stood abreast with developing
countries and is a reliable friend of developing nations.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister praised the good relations between Togo
and China, saying that his nation values its cooperation with
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
