<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,700-Year Old Wild Tea Tree Discovered in Yunnan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, December 20 (Xinhua) -- A 2,700-year old wild tea tree
in southwest China's Yunnan Province, has been described as the
oldest of its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
It is 1,000 years older than the present "King of Tea Trees",
also found in the province in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
The 2,700-year old tree is 25.5 meters high and has a diameter
of 1.2 m. It was spotted by a group of scientists last month in
Qianjia Village in Zhengyuan County. Close by was a another wild
tea tree, 200 years younger, which is 19.5 m high and has a
diameter of 1.02 m.
</P>
<P>
They are the oldest wild tea trees ever found in the world,
according to experts. The trees are still thriving, despite their
old ages.
</P>
<P>
The trees are in a pristine forest situated 2,100 to 2,500
meters above sea level. The forest where the trees stand covers an
area of 280 hectares, with wild tea trees of a diameter of over 30
cm can be seen everywhere.
</P>
<P>
Simao and Xishuangbanna in south Yunnan are famous tea
production areas. A wild tea tree with an age of over 1,700 years
was found in Menghai County in Xishuangbanna in 1961. It was the
oldest wild tea tree discovered at that that time in the world.
</P>
<P>
The latest discovery provides further proof that Yunnan is the
birth place of tea trees, experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
