<HEADLINE> Clinton Meets Chinese Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today told a visiting Chinese official that he believes it is very
important for the United States and China to keep up high-level
meetings.
</P>
<P>
He said he expected to exchange state visits with Chinese
President Jiang Zemin in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Clinton met and exchanged views on Sino-U.S. relations with Liu
Huaqiu, director of the Foreign Affairs Office of China's State
Council, at the Oval Office in the White House.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Al Gore was also present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Liu conveyed greetings from Jiang and Premier Li Peng to
Clinton and Gore. Clinton and Gore asked Liu to return their
greetings.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the planned exchange of state visits between the
U.S. and Chinese leaders, and Gore's forthcoming visit to China
early next year, represented major progress in relations between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. would do its best to strengthen the good
momentum of the bilateral ties, and take positive measures to
increase the trust between the leaders, governments and peoples of
the two countries, so that the whole world would see that the
United States and China were able to establish a partnership.
</P>
<P>
He said the establishment of a partnership between the U.S. and
China were in the interests of the entire world.
</P>
<P>
Over differences between the two countries, Clinton said the
U.S. was willing to have dialogue and discussions with the Chinese
in a constructive and open manner, so as to find ways of
settlement and to reduce friction.
</P>
<P>
Gore said he was looking forward to his China tour early next
year and to exchanging views with Chinese leaders on issues of
common concern. He believed the visit would help promote the
development of Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
Liu said frequent and direct dialogue and meetings between
U.S. and Chinese leaders would give significant impetus to the
development and improvement of relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the successful meeting between Jiang and Clinton in
Manila last month had produced a very important and positive
impact on Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
He said maintaining healthy and stable relations between the
U.S. and China not only conforms to the fundamental interests of
the two countries, but also benefits peace and stability in the
Asia-Pacific region and the world as a whole, and helps create a
peaceful, stable, prosperous and glorious 21st century.
</P>
<P>
At present, he said, Sino-U.S. relations had a positive
momentum of improvement and offered a good opportunity for further
development and improvement. Both sides should cherish and
maintain the hard-won situation.
</P>
<P>
Of the differences between the two countries, Liu said, both
sides should seek resolutions through consultations. If some could
not be settled in a short time, both sides should seek common
ground while reserving differences.
</P>
<P>
Liu said Chinese leaders welcomed Gore's planned visit to
China, at the invitation of Premier Li.
</P>
<P>
Present at the meeting on the U.S. side were Secretary of State
Warren Christopher, Acting Assistant to the President for National
Security Affairs Samuel Berger, White House Chief of Staff Leon
Panetta and Ambassador to China James Sasser. On the Chinese side
were Ambassador to the U.S. Li Daoyu and Assistant Foreign
Minister Yang Jiechi. 
</P>
