<HEADLINE> China to Salvage Sunken Chinese Warship in Yellow Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists plan to
salvage a warship next year, which was sunk by the Japanese navy
in the Yellow Sea off the coast of northern China a century ago,
according to a newspaper report.
</P>
<P>
Approved by the State Bureau of Cultural Relics, a special
office responsible for the preparation of the salvage of the
warship "Zhiyuan" has been set up, the overseas edition of the
"People's Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists from the Underwater Archeology Research Office
under the Museum of Chinese History will carry out the technical
side of the project in May, next year.
</P>
<P>
During the Sino-Japanese War (1894-1895), launched by Japan to
annex Korea and invade China, the Chinese navy of the imperial
Qing government suffered heavy losses, which included the sinking
of four warships bought from Western countries.
</P>
<P>
Captain Deng Shichang, who never left his warship "Zhiyuan",
has become a household name in China over the past 100 years, and
his story was the subject of a popular movie.
</P>
<P>
Donggang City in northeast China's Liaoning Province is
planning to build a museum specializing in the Sino-Japanese naval
war to house the salvaged warship and the relics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Foreign Debt Rises to $607.23 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Latin American and Caribbean
countries posted a 3.4 percent growth in foreign debt this year to
607 billion U.S. dollars, from 598 billion in 1995, the lowest
growth rate since 1991.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, the most heavily-debted country in 14 Latin American
and Caribbean countries, has 175 billion U.S. dollars in foreign
debt in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the United Nations Economic Commission
for Latin America and the Caribbean, seven other countries,
Mexico, Argentina, Venezuela, Peru, Colombia, Chile and Ecuador,
each owes more than 10 billion U.S. dollars in foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
The figures range from 160 billion U.S. dollars, which the
second most indebted Mexico owes, to 14.7 billion U.S. dollars
which Ecuador owes.
</P>
<P>
Argentina rank third in the foreign debt nations, which has a
total foreign debt of 96 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Following Chile, which has 26.15 billion U.S. dollars in
foreign debt, Ecuador is the smallest of the eight big debtor
nations.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela and Peru each owes 32.23 billion dollars in foreign
debt, followed by Colombia, which owes 26.15 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua ranks first in the 10 countries of the region who
managed to cut their foreign debt in 1996, which reduced its 10.2
billion dollars of foreign debt by 40 percent to 6.1 billion
dollars. The other nine countries were Chile, Costa Rica,
Dominican Republic, Guatemala, Honduras, Mexico, Nicaragua,
Paraguay, Trinidad and Tobago, and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
The world's top creditors include Japan, which owns 236 billion
dollars in overseas credit or 15 percent of the total credit of
developing countries, America with 147 billion dollars, Germany
with 106 billion and France with 103 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Ruling Partner Demands Expulsion of MPs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 20 (Xinhua) -- A junior ruling partner in
Nepal has asked the lower house to expel two of its own MPs due to
their attitude toward a no-confidence motion against the
three-party government, it was reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The Nepal Goodwill Party (NSP), third partner of the ruling
coalition led by Sher Bahadur Deuba of the Nepali Congress (NC),
registered separate letters at the parliament on Wednesday and
Thursday demanding the expulsion of its lawmakers Anish Ansari and
Hridyesh Tripathi.
</P>
<P>
The two NSP MPs were among the 102 lower house MPs who earlier
signed a petition claiming that they had lost confidence in Prime
Minister Deuba and his government.
</P>
<P>
A special session of the house, called by King Birendra as
requested by the 102 MPs, is scheduled to begin discussions on the
no-confidence motion on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The NSP in its letters to Speaker Ram Chandra Poudyal said
Ansari and Tripathi have abandoned the party and should be
dismissed from the house in accordance with the constitution. The
NSP has three seats in the house.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, dispute between two factions of the second ruling
party, the National Democratic Party (RPP), over the no-confidence
motion escalated Thursday when two RPP leaders issued contrary
orders.
</P>
<P>
RPP President Surya Bahadur Thapa Thursday asked the party's
parliamentary leader Lokendra Bahadur Chand to order all RPP MPs
to vote in favor of the government, while Chand himself at a
meeting directed the MPs to vote against it.
</P>
<P>
Ten of the RPP's 19 lower house MPs including Thapa Thursday
informed Chand in a collective letter that they will vote against
the no-confidence motion.
</P>
<P>
The motion, expected to be tabled jointly by the RPP's Chand
faction and the main opposition party, the Communist Party of
Nepal (United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML), requires a majority vote
of 103 to pass in the 205-seat lower house.
</P>
<P>
Under a private agreement between Chand and the UML, Chand
would lead a new RPP-UML coalition government if the present
NC-led government is ousted by the no-confidence motion, sources
here said.
</P>
<P>
Neither the UML nor the NC, the two largest parties in the
country with 88 and 86 seats respectively in the lower house,
could form a stable government in Nepal without support from the
third largest party, RPP.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
