<HEADLINE> South Korean President Reshuffles Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 20 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Young-sam reshuffled his cabinet today to help revitalize the
economy and strengthen the country's competitiveness in the wake
of its accession to the OECD, a presidential spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Trade minister Park Jae-yoon, criticized for South Korea's
swelling current account deficit, has been replaced by his deputy
Ahn Kwang-koo in one of 10 changes which include eight
ministerial-level portfolios.
</P>
<P>
Kim Yong-chin, chief of administrative coordination at the
prime minister's office, was named science and technology minister
to replace Koo Bohn-young who becomes South Korea's first
ambassador to the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development (OECD). South Korea became the 29th member of the OECD
on December 12.
</P>
<P>
Kang Hyong-uk, from the ruling New Korea Party (NKP), was
appointed head of the Environment Ministry to replace Chung
Chong-teck.
</P>
<P>
Former NKP lawmaker Jeong Si-chae was picked as the new
minister of agriculture and forest to replace Ghang Wun-tae.
</P>
<P>
President Kim named another former NKP lawmaker, Kim Han-kyu,
as the head of the Government Administration Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Shin Kyung-shik, also NKP lawmaker, replaced Kim Deog-ryong as
first state minister for political affairs.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle was also aimed at tightening national security.
</P>
<P>
Song Jong-eui, deputy prosecutor-general of the Supreme Public
Prosecutor's Office, was appointed new legislation minister.
</P>
<P>
Oh Chung-so, first deputy director of the National Security
Planning Agency, was appointed head of the Patriots and Veterans
Affairs Ministry; while Chang Sung, former deputy commander of the
Korea-United States Combined Forces, was picked as chief of the
National Security Council and Emergency Planning Committee.
</P>
