<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Theft Reported to Be on Rise in Bangkok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The number of cars and
motorcycles stolen here has been soaring this year due to the
rising demand for cars on the black markets in neighboring
countries and growing mastery of overcoming car security systems,
a local daily said today.
</P>
<P>
Between January and October this year, the Metropolitan Police
Bureau received 5,089 reports on car or motorcycle theft,
averaging 500 vehicles a month, the newspaper The Nation reported.
</P>
<P>
Police said many of the vehicles stolen in Thailand are sent
across the border, while others are dismantled and sold as spare
parts, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Some orders for the stolen cars even specify the brand and
model of the cars wanted and car thieves could sell stolen
vehicles immediately through smugglers along the border, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
A car worth 40,000 U.S. dollars might be sold at 2,800 to 3,200
dollars and the registration documents of the engine and car
ownership are usually forged, the newspaper quoted city police
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Police officers at the bureau said they are short of manpower
and necessary cooperation between Bangkok and provincial police
agencies in cracking down on car theft.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
