<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Simulate Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 19 (Xinhua) -- United States Energy
Secretary Hazel O'Leary today formally approved a program to
develop new facilities to enable scientists to monitor the
nation's nuclear stockpile and test warheads without exploding
them.
</P>
<P>
The 40 billion U.S. dollar program was unveiled last month
following President Clinton's announced support for the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty. As a result of the treaty, U.S.
nuclear weapons scientists have to find new ways to monitor the
reliability of the devices.
</P>
<P>
The 10-year program will cover the construction of major new
facilities for scientists to conduct various experiments,
including simulating the information they would achieve from
actual tests.
</P>
<P>
The first three new facilities are the National Ignition
Facility and the Contained Firing Facility at Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory outside San Francisco, and the Atlas Facility
at Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The Energy Department said that the Nevada Test Site, where the
United States had conducted its nuclear weapons tests, would be
used for other purposes such as solar device testing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Debt Shrinks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' debt burden in
the first 11 months of the year declined to 5.6 percent of the
Gross National Product (GNP) from 6.5 percent in the same period
of the last year, according to the Philippine Finance Department.
</P>
<P>
For the first 11 months, the government's gross domestic
borrowings totaled 2.55 billion US dollars, 68 million dollars
below the 2.62 billion dollar program for the period.
</P>
<P>
Its external borrowings for the same period amounted to 772.9
million dollars, 419.6 million US dollars higher than the
programmed 353.3 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The government paid 930 million US dollars in foreign debt,
45.6 million US dollars more than the 885 million US dollar
program.
</P>
<P>
In terms of domestic debt the government paid 393 million US
dollars, still below the programmed 417 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The reduction in the government's debt is part of its efforts
to bring down interest rates in the remaining months of the year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, interest payment for foreign debt is expected to
increase next year due to heavy private sector borrowing this
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
