<HEADLINE> Forced Sale Rules on Thai Stock Market Extended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The maintenance margin and
forced sale rules on the Thai stock market have been extended
until June 30 next year to ease investors' worries about forced
sales during the prolonged downturn in share prices.
</P>
<P>
Vicharat Vichit-vadakarn, president of the Association of
Securities Companies, said that temporary suspension of the rules
was impossible as they were in place to stabilize securities
trading.
</P>
<P>
Currently, local brokers require investors who borrow margin
loans to give more money if the value of their purchases drops
below certain a figure, otherwise part of their holding will be
sold to maintain their initial margin above the rate required by
the broker.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that the current maintenance margin in
the country is at 25 percent and that for forced sales is at 15
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
