<HEADLINE> Croat Herzeg-Bosnia State Officially Disbanded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, December 19 (Xinhua) -- The Bosnian Croat republic
"Herzeg-Bosnia" officially ceased to exist today, the president of
the Muslim-Croat federation, Kresimer Zubak said.
</P>
<P>
"The government and the ministries of Herceg-Bosna
(Herzeg-Bosnia) will no longer function," Zubak said in a letter
to Carl Bildt, the international Bosnian peace coordinator.
</P>
<P>
The Muslims had met requirements of the Croats to hand over
relevant powers to the federation, so the Croats agreed to abolish
the existence of their self-proclaimed "Croatian Republic of
Herzeg-Bosnia," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Croat state, which was not recognized by anyone but
Croatia, was to have been dismantled by August 31 under an
agreement signed two weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian Croats, however, did not comply then as promised,
and the southwestern city of Mostar effectively continues to be a
divided city.
</P>
<P>
Under U.S. pressure, Muslims and Croats signed a federation
agreement in Washington in 1994 after fighting each other for a
year. But both kept their own government institutions.
</P>
<P>
The federation was confirmed by the Dayton peace agreement
signed last year, under which the country was to be divided into
two entities, with the Bosnian Serb republic as the other half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0223 </DOCNO>
