<HEADLINE> Panamanians Urge Making of Day to Mourn Victims of Invasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Several Panamanian popular
organizations are asking the government to make December 20th, the
anniversary of the 1989 U.S. invasion of Panama, the "National
Mourning Day" as a homage to victims of the invasion.
</P>
<P>
Among the organizations are the Union of Construction Workers,
the Center of Studies and Teaching of Panama, Alternate Legal
Assistance of Panama, the November 29th Revolutionary Students
Front and the Independent Students Movement.
</P>
<P>
On December 20, 1989, some 27,000 U.S. troops broke into Panama
to start a six-day military invasion of the central Amercian
country, killing hundreds of Panamanians, mainly civilians.
</P>
<P>
The then Panamanian ruler General Manuel Antonio Noriega was
arrested by the Americans and taken to the U.S. for trials on
drug-trafficking charges. He was later sentensed to 40 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
"The invasion was a catastrophe for the people and country, in
terms of economic crisis, destruction of businesses,
infrastructure, housing and loss of human lives," said Richardo
Castille, the leader of the Movement of Organizations Against
U.S. Military Bases.
</P>
<P>
Organizations participating in the commemoration activities of
the invasion plan to hold "a great black march" Friday which,
according to the organizers, will represent the mourning of the
Panamanian people.
</P>
<P>
The march would start at 4:00 p.m. (local time), from the Plaza
Porras in downtown Panama City, and end at the El Chorrillo
section, known as a martyr's neighborhood, said the organizers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
