<HEADLINE> Transport on Lancang-Mekong River Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Yunnan Province in southwest
China is expected to transport 60,000 tons of import and export
commodities this year through the Lancang-Mekong River, an
increase of 50 percent over the figure of last year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of November, the province had shipped 53,000 tons of
goods through the river, which runs through several countries
including China, Myanmar, and Laos.
</P>
<P>
China mainly exports fruits, garlic, daily-use articles,
building materials, and tobacco, and imports tropical fruits,
grain and plastic products.
</P>
<P>
Cargo transport on the river is anticipated to further increase
when China signs a navigation deal with Myanmar in 1997. There has
been a navigation agreement between China and Laos.
</P>
<P>
China is now busy improving the river course to pave the way
for the accomodation of 100-ton ships. 
</P>
