<HEADLINE> World Bank Grants Loan for Indonesia's Iodization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 20 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank will provide a
28.5 million US dollars loan to Indonesia for intensifying the
iodine deficiency control program efforts in the country, Antara
news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to a news release issued by the bank on Wednesday,
the loan would help the Indonesian project worth 45.3 million
dollars by developing policies to increase the supply, quality and
consumption of iodized salt.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government will finance the remaining 16.8
million dollars, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank estimates about one-third of Indonesia's 195
million people live in iodine deficient areas resulting in the
high iodine deficiency rate.  
</P>
