<HEADLINE> Poland, France, Germany Discuss Enlargement of EU, NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, December 19 (Xinhua) -- The Foreign Ministers of
Poland, France and Germany met here today to discuss the planned
enlargement of the European Union (EU) and the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO), the Polish Press Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
They also announced a summit between the three heads of state
next July.
</P>
<P>
Talks focussed on the process of integration for countries of
the former Soviet-led bloc which now are aiming to join the EU and
NATO.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers discussed a French proposal for a
European conference in 1998 which would gather all countries
wishing to join the EU.
</P>
<P>
France and Germany supported Poland's membership of NATO, the
visiting officials said.
</P>
<P>
During their one-day visit, French Foreign Minister Herve de
Charette and his German counterpart Klaus Kinkel met several
Polish leaders, including President Aleksander Kwasniewski and
Prime Minister Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicz.
</P>
<P>
Poland, France and Germany formed the so-called Weimar
triangle, a cooperation forum set up in 1991 at the end of the
Cold War.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski said he attached great importance to the Weimar
triangle. "It enables us to put into practice active cooperation
between countries that came from different blocs," he said.
</P>
<P>
This is the sixth meet of the foreign ministers from the three
countries and the second to be held in Warsaw. 
</P>
</TEXT>
