<HEADLINE> Beijing to Tackle Traffic Jam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 20 (Xinhua) -- A group of people's deputies
have urged the Beijing municipal government to "do something about
the traffic jams", a real headache of 12 million residents of the
Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The deputies who were elected to speak for Beijingers conveyed
their complaints to city Party Secretary Wei Jianxing and acting
mayor Jia Qinglin during a face-to-face talk on Wednesday, "China
Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Traffic jams are commonplace throughout Beijing and have
become a threat to the normal lives of residents," the report
quoted the deputies as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy to know that Beijing will overhaul 255 major
roads by the year 2000. But how about those small lanes?" said
Yang Zhounan, a deputy from the People's Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
Yang suggested that the municipal government should be
persistently tough on pedlars who block the lanes and the randomly
parked cars which always manage to block the backstreets
connecting lanes.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very surprised to know that the computer system used by
the Municipal Traffic Administrative Center was imported in the
early 1980s," blamed Nie Li, a member of National People's
Congress Standing Committee, the country's legislative body.
</P>
<P>
Such a computer system surely cannot react to accidents
efficiently, she added, urging the government to invest more in
road management.
</P>
<P>
The city administrators have said that they will seriously
consider the legislators' suggestions and give each of them an
answer, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report was accompanied by a photo, which highlighted
vehicles stream in both directions on and alongside the Beitaiping
Bridge on the Third Ring Road in Beijing's Haidian District during
rush hours.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has at least one million motor vehicles and eight
million non-motor-vehicles, mainly bicycles. Despite huge
government financial support in building roads, the growth of
roads are far behind that of the vehicles, said an earlier report
of "Beijing Daily".
</P>
<P>
Most of the trunk ways within the third ring road are now in
the state of saturation or over-saturation, it said.
</P>
<P>
The increased volume of traffic and the increasing number of
traffic violations are making traffic congestion worse in the
capital, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
