<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientist Wins International Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Sheng Jinzhang, academician of
the Chinese Academy of Sciences and researcher at the Nanjing
Institute of Geological Paleontology, has received the Cushman
Award from the U.S.-based Cushman Foundation for his outstanding
achievements on the research of sarcodina.
</P>
<P>
Sarcodina is a sort of ancient unicellular organisms.
</P>
<P>
The Cushman Foundation was established in 1950 and was named
after Joseph A. Cushman, a well-known international biologist. The
Cushman Award is the world top prize in the field of paleontology.
</P>
<P>
Sheng is China's first scientist winning such an award.
</P>
<P>
Sarcodina, living one million years ago, had hard shells with
many holes and 99.9 percent of them lived in seas and they easily
became fossils.
</P>
<P>
The research of sarcodina plays an important role for oil and
gas prospecting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
