<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Branch of Yangtze to Be Clear Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 20 (Xinhua) -- A river in east China's
Jiangsu Province is expected to be clear again after some 500
million yuan has been spent to treat it over the last dozen years.
</P>
<P>
The 120-km long Qinhuai River divide into two branches when it
reaches Nanjing, capital of Jiangsu Province, joining again before
flowing into the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
A part of Qinhuai River in Nanjing used to be known as one of
the most bustling downtown areas in ancient China.
</P>
<P>
The river pollution treatment project started in 1985. Local
authorities attach great importance to the project, and the
general director of the project is headed by the mayor. Besides
allocations from the central government, local government has
collected 450 million yuan for the project.
</P>
<P>
The Jiangxinzhou Sewage Treatment Plant, the crucial part of
the project, has been completed recently and has gone into
operation, bringing pollution in the river under control. The
plant has a capacity of treating 260,000 cubic km of waste water
daily.
</P>
<P>
The whole project comprises 28 sub-projects, 21 of which have
been completed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
