<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Sign of Happy Ending in Peruvian Hostage Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, December 19 (Xinhua) -- About 400 dignitaries spent the
third day of captivity in Japanese ambassador's residence in Lima
without knowing when and how they would be released.
</P>
<P>
Leftist guerrillas broke into the compound Tuesday night and
took hostage all the people there celebrating Japanese Emperor
Akihito's birthday.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Ambassador Anthony Vincent refused to speculate about
the resolution of the standoff.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the drama could come to a peaceful end at a new
conference, he said: "I'm sorry. I can't get into that."
</P>
<P>
The ambassador was among those trapped in the building by the
Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA) rebels, but was released
late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He and three other ambassadors were designated to go between
the two sides of the standoff.
</P>
<P>
He said all female hostages had been released and the rest of
the captives were being treated "correctly" by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, armed with guns and grenades, threatened to execute
the hostages one by one if the government didn't release their
imprisoned comrades.
</P>
<P>
The rebels had set free about 170 people Tuesday night, mostly
women and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
President Alberto Fujimori's government remains silent over the
crisis in face of conflicting international pressures.
</P>
<P>
The United States asked Fujimori not to give in to terrorist
blackmail, but Japan cautioned him on any action that could
threaten the lives of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Minister Yukihito Ikeda is in Lima to help
solve the problem and the Washington has also sent security agents.
</P>
<P>
It is still unclear how the rebels, only about 20 in number,
were able to break into the residence and round up so many people.
</P>
<P>
Vincent said he heard an explosion and then the rebels rushed
in, shooting in the air and yelling.
</P>
<P>
The MRTA guerrillas are the second largest anti-government
group in the country, after the Shining Path.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's attack was a heavy blow to the government who claimed
that the MRTA rebels had already been defeated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
