<HEADLINE> A Chinese Farmer And His Sand Control Stock Company (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1984, the household contract responsibility system was
introduced in his hometown, and the state Three North Shelterbelt
System Project was also launched.
</P>
<P>
No one in the village at that time saw it as a golden
opportunity except him. He contracted to afforest 200 hectares of
the state-owned desert, together with six other households.
</P>
<P>
He said: "To buy the samplings we sold all that could be sold,
but our efforts reaped rewards due to our hard work, as well as
the government's support.
</P>
<P>
"The following year, most of my neighbors contracted to plant
trees in the desert and it was not very long before our
surrounding environment became greener and greener.
</P>
<P>
"Then came the most exciting moment when I signed a contract
with the local government to establish a sand-control company to
which stock, new as it was, was introduced, and that was in 1987.
</P>
<P>
"Our company developed really fast, within four years we had
covered all the desert in our township with green trees, and the
profits hugely increased year after year," he said, "and now we
are considering enlarging our business by contracting more sandy
lands".
</P>
<P>
He said he has the confidence to lead his company to a brighter
future.
</P>
<P>
"Now, the sorry stories that happened often when I was a child
will never happen again since the surrounding flowing-sand have
been controlled by the trees", he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Chinese Farmer And His Sand-Control Stock Company (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 20 (Xinhua) -- A farmer who was once blown 10
kilometers in a sandstorm told officials in this Chinese capital
how he set out to tame the desert that threatened his home village.
</P>
<P>
Sitting beside the country's Minister of Forestry, the ordinary
farmer gave a speech to dozens of officials from forestry
departments across the country.
</P>
<P>
The farmer Shi Guangyin, 48, is from a small village in
northwest China's Shaanxi Province where the Maowusu, one of
China's largest desert stretches.
</P>
<P>
During the last 12 years, Shi and his neighbors have
successfully transformed more than 4,000 hectares of desert into a
thriving oasis, with a tree coverage of over 91 percent.
</P>
<P>
"When I was in my childhood, I often saw our houses being
submerged by flowing sands, so we had to move frequently," he told
his audience.
</P>
<P>
"Once when I was herding sheep in the field, the sand-storm
came and I was blown to another village 10 kilometers away, and a
five-year-old child even lost his life during that sand-storm".
</P>
<P>
"That was when I made up my mind to control the sand when I
grew up", he said.
</P>
<P>
"At the age of 20, I walked 100 kilometers to learn sand-tree
planting technologies and after that I spent three years to make
the first oasis in the desert near my village".
</P>
<P>
He added: "This greatly encouraged me and I started to know
firmly that we can change our living conditions through our own
efforts."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
