<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High-Grade Road Network Built in Jiangsu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 20 (Xinhua) -- Two grade-one highways
connecting this capital city of east China's Jiangsu province with
other cities in the province have recently been open to traffic.
</P>
<P>
By now nine of the 13 cities directly under the provincial
government have been connected by high-grade roads, and
expressways have been built linking the five cities of Nanjing,
Zhenjiang, Changzhou, Wuxi and Suzhou.
</P>
<P>
The newly built Nanjing-Lianyungang Grade-one Highway is 306.5
kilometers long and links three cities in Jiangsu and neighboring
on Anhui province; while the Nanjing-Nantong Highway is 243 km
long and links the four cities of Nanjing, Yangzhou, Taizhou and
Nantong.
</P>
<P>
The two highways cut the time for a journey from Nanjing to two
cities by half.
</P>
<P>
They represent part of the province's endeavors to improve road
network in the part north of the Yangtze River, a traditionally
less-developed area.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, Jiangsu has invested 7.326 billion yuan in building
68.8 km of expressways, 340 km of grade-one highways in that part
of the province.
</P>
<P>
Xu Huaqiang, director of the Provincial Communications Bureau,
said two other high-grade roads from Nanjing to Xuzhou and
Yancheng are also being built, and all the cities directly under
the provincial government will be connected with high-grade roads
by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The high-grade highways in Jiangsu are an important part of
China's national highway network, Xu added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
