<HEADLINE> United States Urged to Pay U.N.Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Chilean Foreign Minister Jose
Miguel Insulza today urged the United States to pay its debt to
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister expressed hope that the new general
secretary of the United Nations, Ghanian Kofi Annan, "will have
more support than the previous one, mainly from those countries
that have to pay their quotas."
</P>
<P>
Insulza was referring to the United States, which owes
approximately 1.4 billion U.S. dollars to the United Nations in
unpaid quotas.
</P>
<P>
Kofi Annan will succeed Egyptian Boutros-Boutros Ghali, whose
re-election as head of the organization was vetoed by the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Ghali had called on the U.S. authorities to have the debt paid.
</P>
<P>
The new U.N. general secretary will assume his post on January
1 of 1997.
</P>
<P>
"We consider Annan's election very satisfactory. Annan assures
the continuity within the organization -- something very
important," said Insulza. 
</P>
</TEXT>
