<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Abuse among Teen-agers on Increase in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Illegal drug abuse among
teen-agers in the United States is increasing with the continuing
resurgence in marijuana use, according to a nationwide survey.
</P>
<P>
The study of 50,000 eighth, 10th and 12th graders found that
the proportion of drug use in the previous year among eighth
graders has more than doubled since 1991, from 11 percent to 24
percent. Among 10th graders, it has risen from 20 percent to 38
percent. And for 12 graders it has risen from 27 percent to 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
Marijuana use has increased sharply since the early 1990s.
Eighteen percent of eighth graders said they had used marijuana in
the previous year, compared with just 6 percent in 1991.
Thirty-four percent of 10th graders said they had used it in the
previous year, compared with 15 percent in 1991. And 36 percent of
high school seniors said so, compared with 22 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 5 percent of high school seniors surveyed said they used
marijuana every day, compared with 2 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The findings indicated the increase in marijuana use is
accompanied by teen-agers' casual attitudes toward the drug and
their belief that it is not harmful.
</P>
<P>
Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala, who released
the survey today, said the Clinton administration was doing its
best to send out the message about the dangers of drugs, alcohol
and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
The secretary stressed that the aggressive fight to change
current drug trends should include increasing teen-agers'
awareness about the dangers of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
Several groups of scientists and researchers called on the
government to re-evaluate its drug education programs, saying zero
tolerance policies alone are too limited and teens should be given
accurate information about why drugs are harmful.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted by the University of Michigan with the
support by research grants from the National Institute on Drug
Abuse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
