<DOCNO> XIE19961220.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Hails Nuclear Safety Cooperation with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 19 (Xinhua) -- France said today that it is
satisfied with cooperations between the Group of Seven (G-7) most
industrialized nations and Russia and Ukraine in nuclear safety in
1996.
</P>
<P>
France, which took over presidency of G-7 on January 1, 1996,
saw the Moscow summit in April held by G-7 countries and Russia on
prevention of nuclear hazards, and the closing of a reactor in the
Chernobyl nuclear center by Ukraine on November 30, as two mile
stones of such achievements.
</P>
<P>
Claude Mandil, General Director in Charge of Energy and Primary
Materials of the Ministry of Industry, described the assessment by
France on efforts to keep nuclear safety and security by former
Soviet countries as "very satisfying."
</P>
<P>
He said that the agreement signed in 1995 between G-7 and
Ukraine over the closing of Chernobyl nuclear center was put into
work from the beginning of 1996, and was partially achieved with
the closing of Reactor One of Chernobyl on November 30.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Ukraine has been restructuring its energy
industry by building conventional energy projects with 900 million
U.S. dollars of loans from G-7 countries.
</P>
<P>
Mandil also said that the agreement signed in Moscow in April
between G-7 countries and Russia over nuclear safety measures is
yielding results.
</P>
<P>
He cited as examples the coming into force on October 24 of the
International Convention on Nuclear Safety, the signing by Russia
and Ukraine of the Vienna Convention on Civil Nuclear
Responsibility, and the common program on fighting trafficking of
nuclear materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
