<HEADLINE> Rwanda to Hold First Trial of People Accused of Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda will hold on December 30
its first trial of people accused of committing the 1994 genocide
against the Tutsis and moderate Hutus, in which at least half a
million people were killed.
</P>
<P>
This was announced today by Jariel Rutaremara, president of the
Specialized Chamber of the First Investigation Tribunal of Kigali,
in the Rwandan capital, said the Agence France Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
"The first hearings of December 30 concern two cases, one
being about the former substitute of procurator of Kigali, Silace
Munyagishali, the other about the counselor of a commune of the
prefecture of rural Kigali, Theodomire Ruzirabwoba," said the
judge.
</P>
<P>
He said that both of them are accused of genocide and crimes
against humanity, and could be given death sentence.
</P>
<P>
He also said that hearings of four other cases will be held
early next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
