<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Year 1996 Sees Record Number of Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 19 (Xinhua) -- The year 1996 has seen a
record number of U.S. enterprises merging at record pace with
a staggering value of 537 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Prominent among them is Computer Associates international Inc,
one of the world's largest software companies, which in a buying
spree bought Cheynenne Software Inc., a maker of mass storage
software for business computers. The merger is the third largest in
software history trailing only Computer Associates Acquisition of
Legent and the Interanional business Machine Corporation's three
billion U.S. dollar purchase of the Lotus Development Corporation
last year.
</P>
<P>
Other striking examples are Mattel, the world's largest toy
maker, which merged with Tyco, America's third largest toy
company; CSX Corporation, a big railroad that blankets the
Southeast, Middle Atlantic and eastern Midwest, which acquired
Conrail Inc, the freight railroad that dominates The Northeast.
The deal valued at 8.4 billion U.S. dollars is the biggest yet in
cascade of deals that has been combining railroads since the
deregulation of the industry in the 1980's.
</P>
<P>
The transactions took place largely in such businesses as
banking, retailing, telecommunications and health care which found
themselves unable to compete by means of raising prices or
increasing production. Taking telecommunication as example. Four
mergers have occurred since the beginning of this year with total
value of 73.2 billion U.S. dollars. By so doing, the businesses
reduced their costs and met requirements in markets.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts attributed the quickening of businesses'
merger to intensified competition, deregulation by the Federal
Government, bullish stocks and slow growth of earnings. Modest
economic growth, no visible inflation and no change of interest
rate are also factors contributing to enterprises taking steps
towards merger.
</P>
<P>
Economists described the merger as a main trend in U.S.
business activities and they expect more enterprises to merge in
the coming year in the struggle for survival and growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
