<HEADLINE> French Union Leader Resigns from Communist Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Louis Viannet, General Secretary
of the powerful French trade union Confederation Generale du
Travail (CGT), today officially submitted his resignation from the
leading nation bureau of the French Communist Party (PCF).
</P>
<P>
Viannet told 1,100 PCF delegates at the on-going 29th Congress
of the PCF that his quitting the PCF leadership is ``a wishable
and necessary move'' which is aimed at separating more clearly the
function of the union from that of the party.
</P>
<P>
He denied that there are differences of view between him and
the PCF National Secretary, Robert Hue, or that he disagrees with
the ``work undertaken by the party.''
</P>
<P>
The Agence France Presse (AFP) said that the resignation of
Viannet from PCF leadership is a logical evolution of the
relationship between the union and the party, whose layout was
inherited from the Third Internationale.
</P>
<P>
CGT's close relationship with the PCF is still maintained, as
is shown by the make-up of the leading confederate bureau of GCT,
among whose 16 members are eight PCF members, said AFP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
