<HEADLINE> Rallies Supporting Milosevic Staged throughout Serbia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 19 (Xinhua) -- Rallies offering support to
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic and condemning the
subservient attitude by a part of the opposition parties were held
throughout Serbia on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to Tanjug news agency, these rallies were organized
by local branches of the ruling Socialist Party of Serbia (SPS)
headed by Milosevic to counter against the opposition coalition's
daily protest demonstrations in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Addressing some 20,000 people who had gathered in Krusevac in
central Serbia, leader of the local board of the SPS Miloje
Mihajlovic said that, at a time when it was crucial to meet the
obligations assumed under the Dayton peace accords, some power
wielders in the world had spurred the opposition to stage rallies,
accusing authorities of the violation of human rights and
democratic principles.
</P>
<P>
"These power wielders have found allies in a group of traitors
who want to seize power at all costs," Tanjug quoted Mihajlovic as
saying. He said leaders of the opposition coalition Zajedno had
run against the people's will and through foreign assistance to
wreck and sell the country.
</P>
<P>
Referring to protest marches by supporters of the coalition
Zajedno, Sabac Mayor Marko Maksimovic said, "The marches through
Serbia do not recognize efforts by legally elected bodies or
authorities elected through the Serbian people's will."
</P>
<P>
In Backa Palanka in Serbia's northern province of Vojvodina,
about 10,000 people gathered in the town offering support to
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
The rally, held under the slogan "Serbia will not be ruled by a
foreign hand," expressed dissatisfaction with what they called,
"aggressive, undemocratic and anti-patriotic activity of the
coalition Zajedno."
</P>
<P>
The rally said the opposition coalition used the results of the
November polls only as an excuse for its activity aimed at
creating chaos in the country and overthrowing the political
system.
</P>
<P>
A pro-government rally, organized by the local board of the
SPS, was also staged in Gornji Milanovac. The demonstration
organizers sent a telegram to Milosevic, stressing that the people
wanted all outstanding issues to be resolved within legal
institutions and not under the flags of states whose presence in
Serbia had always meant bloodshed, war, discord among brothers and
ever new blackmails. 
</P>
</TEXT>
