<HEADLINE> U.S. Dispatches Envoy to Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Warren Christopher said on Thursday that he is dispatching senior
envoy Dennis Ross to the Middle East for consultations with the
Israelis and Palestinians, in an effort to salvage stalled peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a year-end news conference, Christopher said: "I
still have confidence in the peace process. The United States
cannot fail to assist the parties and stand by the parties as they
take risks for peace."
</P>
<P>
But in contrast with President bill Clinton's criticism this
week of Israel's expanding settlements in the West Bank,
Christopher urged the Palestinians to respond to Israeli overtures
and conclude a long-elusive agreement on Hebron as a step toward a
broader peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"The Israelis have made some moves and it's time for the
Palestinians to reciprocate," he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel was reported to have offered to reopen a main street in
the West Bank city that was closed last year as a deterrent to
violence.
</P>
<P>
Christopher, however, reiterated that Israel's settlements
policy concerned him.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's government decided
last week to revive subsidies and tax break for Jewish settlers on
the West Bank and in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
The effect, Christopher said, is to "move ahead of where the
parties are now." 
</P>
</TEXT>
