<HEADLINE> UN Council Condemns Taking of Hostages in Lima </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 19 (Xinhua) -- The UN Security Council
"vigorously condemn the occupation of the residence of the
Ambassador of Japan in Lima, Peru, and the taking of hostages by
terrorist elements," Council President Paolo Fulci of Italy said
here today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to press, the Italian ambassador said, "This
intolerable act constitutes also an assault against the
international community as a whole."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council has always firmly condemned terrorist
acts, whatever the circumstances, in the most unequivocal terms,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Such acts constitute a violation of basic principles of
international law and of human rights, as well as an attempt to
jeopardize the democratic system and threaten peace and security,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The members of the Council express their solidarity with the
governments of Peru and Japan, as well as with the governments of
all countries concerned, and appeal for the immediate release of
all officials, diplomats and other persons being held hostage, he
said.
</P>
<P>
A group of guerrillas took hundreds of international
dignitaries hostage on Tuesday night when the Japanese ambassador
hosted a reception in honor of his Emperor's birthday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
